Once they are safe, the rest is your decision.nnI pray that you return to offer your blade, but you've already done so much that this town will forever be in your debt.nnPlease, hurry. Coldun approaches and we cannot be caught off guard.

Several villagers have not yet left this village. I need you to make sure they get out of here alive! nnThey should be in the buildings in this village. Go, give them persuasion so they may live for another day.

There is a curate of Arkay living in a house just to the northeast of here. His name is Marcel and he has been a good friend to my parents. He would be invaluable in our cause, but he has been cut off from Camlorn and us by bandits.

There was a ranger who knew all of the hiding places in this forest that passed through here a bit ago. He was headed past Camlorn, and some of the soldiers who came north said they saw his camp in the ruins near the city.
And you would know, I suppose?
I'd like to see him try.
You've diminished the goblins' magic. Well done.  That will go a long way towards pushing them away from Grayborne.nnTo truly dissuade them, we need a particular artifact: the legendary Howling Pipe.

Inquisitor Roche's men took the Howling Pipe from a sister of the Wyrd they... apprehended.nnYou can get close to him. We cannot. Take this powder and throw it in his face. It should stun him long enough for you to get the pipe back.
What you lack in wisdom you make up for in nerve!nnYour meddling in the matter of Elsie Dolban made an enemy of me.  GUARDS!
I know quite a few, but they're all terrible.
A skeleton walks into a bar and asks for an ale...and a mop.
I could tell you about the well, but that's a dry joke.
I named my pet salamander "Tiny" because he's my newt.
You're right, of course... *I* must return.  *You*, however, can stay here and rot, for all I care...nnNow give me back my robe!
I'm doing well, thank you. At least, for now.
He's back with King Sebastien in the manor.

Do I look like a lord or baron to you? I'm a simple solder: all they told me was great guests were coming. Some new treaty, no doubt, King Sebastien and King Ranser making some deal under the Emissary's watchful eye.

Why, the Adamant Crown's our grand alliance! Eight kings and one High King, bound in an indestructible ring. All High Rock's joined the High King's union, conquered without a fight. It's unnatural, I tell you: to stand beside Redguards and Orcs…

You are new here, aren't you? Sebastien is King of Northmoor. That's this whole realm if you're confused, and he rules from Camlorn - the city where you're standing, in case you didn't know. A fine king, even if an Adamant Crown is higher than his.

Oron is his name, I think. Some fine Redguard nobleman from Hammerfell across the sea, the High King's man. I hear he's leading the search for the assassin. He needs all the help he can muster - if you'd help set things right, seek him out.

Who was King Ranser you mean. Ranser was King in Shornhelm to the north. He warred with Northmoor for years, 'till the High King made him and King Sebastien brothers. Many in Northmoor found that hard to bear. Seems someone's done something about it.

Ah, there's a tale. The High King, he's a clever one — he has nine daughters, and married them all off to forge his alliance. Northmoor, Shornhelm, Evermor, Wayrest… all have queens from Hammerfell. Politics! I've no head for it.

Fahara'jad is his name, King of Hammerfell and the Redguards.  He forged the Adamant Crown.  He rules from Sentinel, across the Illiac Bay.  He bound all High Rock to his will without a single battle.
She's the daughter of King Fahara'jad.  Their marriage solidified the alliance between Northmoor and Hammerfell.
Sadly, no. I just pay attention to the winds.
When the winds pick up, my eyes get watery and I can barely breathe. For now, though, I'm fine.
I am tired! M'lady doesn't have near enough hands for her holdings! Never a minute to m'self, that's what.
We live in interesting times, traveler. I wouldn't darken your sleep with some of the tales I've heard.
Those thieving little Murklings are known to do more than just steal. They aren't above cutting your throat should they catch you unawares.
A cousin of mine has had several run-ins with them. And he bears the scars from their last meeting. Don't trust any Murkling. If one is close enough to speak with you, strike first!
My wife wouldn't leave the cottage lest our son return home and find it empty. Then she ran off, too. That leaves all the work to me...not that my son did much work to begin with.
Alert!  Alert!  Unbeliever in our midst!
I've had cows with more energy than he ever showed! At least my daughter will marry a good crofter to take over the farm work.

If you ask me, he's run off to join the Murklings, and good riddance to him. Always dawdling about his chores. We'll see how he likes having to steal his daily bread instead of doing honest work for it!
Just my thoughts, and I'd as soon forget them. Tell me something: what do you know of the Lion Guard?
As have I. You guard your words, which shows great wisdom. I have heard many things about the Lion Guard that trouble me, at least a little.
There may be some misinformation being spread about them. They have always been good to me. If only things were simpler, eh?
Some say their motives are not pure. Others say that only the doubters are impure. I no longer know what to believe, and that is why you find me lost in thought.
Someone from the...Magis Order. I think. I'm not sure. It's hard to tell sometimes.
I...I can't remember. It's probably not important. Listen, please say nothing of this to anyone. I must be imagining things. Please!
Wouldn't you be? They come in, looking and touching and asking questions...sometimes more than once in a day! It's distracting me from my shop!
As a shopkeeper, I hear many things. My sources, however, depend upon my discretion. You'll hear no gossip from me.
I will speak to King Sebastian about Countess Virolynn. I need you, my friend, to speak with Baron Winoc.
You will find Baron Winoc in the northeastern corner of Camlorn.

Baron Winoc is a respected nobleman of Camlorn. I hear he is an honorable man, prominent in High Rock's militia. His defense of Northmoor doubtless alerts him to any threats to the kingdom: he may know much indeed.

The Magis are battlemages, defenders of Northmoor. They say they're our protectors, hunting hidden evils. They've become a legion of thugs, oppressing common folk at the slightest suspicion. Of course, to speak against them is proof of wrongdoing!

My sisters and I are against harming anyone, yet the truth remains: These goblins are causing trouble. They will only cause more.nnFrighten them with the pipe. After that, perhaps killing their leader will finally convince them.

Not directly, not yet. The Hands of Northmoor are the original militia, who protected us of old. The Magis Order was founded to reinforce the Hands, but now eclipse them. But I've heard some among the Hands grow tired of their arrogance...

Well, I'd not want to burden you with troubles, but if you insist... Times are grim, the worst I've seen in a score of winters. Werewolves in Dwynnen, bandits on the road, and ravening ghouls here in Ykalon! All the while, strife ties our hands.

The way I heard it, the north is crawling with werewolves! The entire village of Westry in Dwynnen has been lost to the beasts, and Crosswych is sore beset. But that's not the end of it - wild packs are killing loggers in the woods outside Camlorn!

Aye, the dead walk in Northmoor! Ghouls by the hundreds attack from the north, hungry for our very souls! The Magis Order can keep them at bay, but for how long? If you're brave enough, seek Commander Blarae at the Redoubt. He needs help.

When the cat's away, the rats shall have their day. The troubles have drawn the Magis Order away, and the bandits grow bold. The roads aren't safe, for the first time in years! If traders can't bring goods to Camlorn, we'll all be paupers by winter.

You've not heard of them? The Magis Order hunts witches and slays monsters. They were founded to defend Northmoor and they've done a fine job; I've never felt safer.  But some say they go too far. And now, I fear they have too many foes to face.

How you view them depends upon many things. Some say they bring hope to the simple folk who've struggled beneath the Magis Order's dictates. Others say they're little better than bandits. I've never had trouble with them, myself.

Look around you. The Magis Order, founded to protect us from evil, has grown so zealous that they can't tell enemies from friends. There are some calling themselves the Hands of Northmoor who've tired of them. Their feud may lead to civil war.

There were a group of Kings who ruled High Rock during a period of peace and great prosperity.  Recognizing their rule would someday conclude they sought to deny fate and extend their rule.  They became vampires.
Precisely.  I was commanded to withdraw Northmoor from the Adamant Crown.  When I refused soldiers appeared on Shornhelm's border and Ranser visited Camlorn to personally encourage my compliance.
One of them, yes.  Fear not, I walk openly beneath the sun.  nnHigh Rock continued to prosper under the shadow cabinet until High King Fahara'jad's sought to forge the Adamant Crown.
Nay, I dare say we have enough time to get help from one.nnYou must make haste and get to either. The hourglass sands are quickly falling and I fear what shall happen when they are all but gone.
The good Baron told me to keep an eye out for the courier, and for you as well.

Adwyn his name is, and he's in trouble. The Magis dogs were waiting for him, and took him soon as he arrived. They've got him in a storehouse east of town, holding him tight: a brace of Watchers guard the place, threatening any who come near.
Inquisitor Roche ordered his arrest.  I am sure Roche wants to retrieve the sword before the Hands - to protect Averos from the murder charges.
I am afraid not.  Perhaps if you were to befriend Roche, earn his trust, you may learn where the courier is being held.  My scouts will continue searching.
You went to Daenia in pursuit of the murder weapon which was used to slay King Ranser. You were supposed to speak to either Roche or Brennoc, what did you discover?
I'd heard this through my contacts. So the second courier sent you to Countess Virolynn who was attacked by a werewolf.  Did you slay the fell beast?
I'd heard this through my contacts. So the second courier sent you to Countess Virolynn who was attacked by a werewolf.  Did you slay the fell beast?
I'd heard this through my contacts. So the second courier sent you to Countess Virolynn who was attacked by a werewolf.  Did you look after the Countess?
I'd heard this through my contacts. So the second courier sent you to Countess Virolynn who was attacked by a werewolf.  Did you look after the Countess?

These are ill times. There's enemies at the gates of Eagle's Watch, and now Crosswych is besieged by werewolves? It is time to put this new alliance to the test. Give this missive to Godwin. It will allow him to request help from Fahara'jad himself.
I'm ruined, surely! My entire shipment lost to howling specters. I've no money to hire a caravan to Wayrest or Daggerfall, and I'll be dipped in tar before I walk that road alone. I'm trapped here.

It's simple enough. Folk are so busy squabbling about the Hands and Order no one will raise a finger. Danain's the only one with his head on straight, but his men are too busy fighting other evils or bracing for war. I can't decide what to do.

I saw them on the road east of here. We were passing a ruin when they came upon us like a chill wind. All my caravan hands fled in terror, and the horses and oxen broke free and ran! Beware that place - death dwells there.

Who knows? They made an awful racket, howling about doom and pain. One shouted something about Ulorion being cursed - he founded the Magis Order, you know. I don't see how that can be - King Ranser put a sword through Ulorion twenty years ago.

Murder! And a king, no less. Hospitality is broken, the king is disgraced, and who knows how it will end? This was to be an age of peace, but the old feuds still burn too hot. Now there will be war with Shornhelm. Blood from blood.

We Bretons have always fought. Daggerfall, Wayrest, Evermor-- we've shed all their blood, and them ours. Why, I can remember the last war agaisnt Shornhelm. Now we're sure to have another. May Stendarr's mercy be upon us all.

It's the Redguards-- the King in Sentinel married off four of his daughters to High Rock Kings. Northmoor, Shornhelm, Evermor, and Wayrest-- all the kings are brothers. Brothers-in-law, to be sure, but brothers all the same. And now that's ruined.

None can tell, that's the real horror. whoever the assassin is, they are long gone. There's an envoy from across the bay-- he's leading the hunt for the killer. If we can bring the killer to justice, maybe Shornhelm can be appeased.
Ranser is dead, slain under King Sebastien's own roof! The King of Shornhelm, dead. I saw his body, with these eyes I did. Poor man had been hacked near to pieces. So much blood...
They say no news is good news. Still, we have plenty of travelers passing through who tell us bits of news now and then. What interests you?
No, not really. Well, perhaps. I don't know who to turn to for advice.
Aldcroft's a good town. Small, but it has everything anyone needs. Traders pass through regularly, so our shops are usually well-stocked.
I've overheard things that I think certain people, if you catch my meaning, would pay handsomely to learn. And yet...

You like the song? A fine ballad, old and true. 'The Winds of Iliac Bay' — the story of how King Fahara'jad of Hammerfell wooed Queen Jenevieve of Wayrest, though a sea lay between them. Know you the tale?

Ah, 'tis a lovely tale. How bitter enemies were reconciled by love. Kynnarth, Goddess of the Winds, bore Fahara'jad's lovesuit all the way from Sentinel to Wayrest, so they say. And now their children have bound nine crowns into an adamant ring.

I will gladly sing another song to you, my friend. But first I must ask for some music of your own. You need not sing: the jingle of coins is the tune I accompany best. Why, even a single coin can have music in it— if it be made of gold…

Ah, I see you've no time or taste for the finer things. So be it! I'm sure so fine a stranger as yourself has far more important matters to attend to. But mark me well: If you would become a legend, best to learn some legends first. Fare thee well.

By the grace of Kynareth, Goddess of the Winds, the Sun King and the Star of Wayrest married. Fahara'jad asked Mara, Mother-Goddess fair, for the means to bring peace to the rest of Iliac Bay. And the Goddess blessed him with daughters nine.

His fair daughters now reign as queens in Evermor, Shornhelm, Gilane, Wayrest, Dragonstar, even here in Northmoor! So many Kings call him father now, all the Baylands are kin. Thus Fahara'jad forged his Adamant Crown, our grand alliance.

Aye, stranger, I do indeed! I am a master bard, and no bards in Tamriel compare to the Breton born! I can sing of Reman's Doom, the Elvish Odes to Sky and Sea, the Saga of the Wilderking, and countless more. Would you care to hear them?
Of course, friend! If you like it, feel free to show your appreciation!
I have no time or patience for anyone who would give these wretches mercy.nnGo bother that fool Brennoc.
We're looked after here, unlike in some places. It's not perfect, but I'm happy. Of course, that could just be the ale speaking, eh?
Well, this is my hometown. Turning in strangers to the Order is one thing, but my neighbors and friends? Still...I could use the coin. I don't know what to do.
You're very perceptive. Why starve until the Countess turns in that traitor, or fend for myself in the wilderness? I'll give the Order what they want and take what I can!
Elsie! She practices witchcraft of a diabolical sort, probably taught to her by those evil Wyrd.

The Beldama Wyrd... never mind that, just go meet her yourself. I'm sure once you speak to her your course will be obvious.  She needs to leave town, immediately. Do this task for me and you will be rewarded...
You are a true hero to Northmoor. I'm certain Averos will be glad of your service. Journey to Eagle's Watch as soon as you can and look for him in its west tower.
Given what you've done for Northmoor, I cannot command you. Very well. Return to me if you decide to travel to Eagle's Watch.
Before you leave, there is one other matter to discuss.
Very well. I trust your judgment. If after speaking with Sebastien you decide to investigate things in Crosswych, speak to me again.

Close one, that. If you'd not arrived to warn us when you did, we'd all have been caught with our pants down. Can't say I'd raise a mug to Averos, but his choice in spies and messengers is beyond reproach. Head back and let Averos know we won.
Westtry? That was our sister village. No one knows what happened to it, or those that do aren't talking. Iven of Westtry might know more. He's on the East side of town.
Who am I? Who am I! nnI am your head on a block if you do not unbind me and free me from this damned place, that's who I am! How dare you ask the great Lord Drugo who he is? Commoners these days…

It's extremely rare! It's what we use as trade in order to survive up here. It's in constant demand by the nearby villages for various potions and mends that they use. In fact, I'd be afraid to think of what would happen without it...
I live in Aldcroft! I'm in the protective custody of my cousin Dilborn, here, one of the leading Hands.
We have proof that Virolynn's chamberlain, Gargast, is a Shornhelm spy, and we will not let him escape by sea! Help us expose Gargast and we'll lift the siege.
The Lion Guard claims that Virolynn's aide, Gargast, is some kind of "spy." It's ridiculous, and besides, who put the Lion Guard in charge? Help us run them off and restore the situation to order.
Our troubles touch more than just Camlorn. Queen Parvani, is...that is, was married to the late King Ranser of Shornhelm. She will be devastated to hear of his death.
My beloved younger sister and I have always been close. When I married, she and I wept together, sad to be parted. When she married and came to Shornhelm, we wept together for joy.
Joy to be near each other again. Shornhelm is not that distant from Northmoor. Indeed, some say it is too close. My poor sister, all alone now.

Then I fear you are too late. Ranser is dead. But wait - you are the one who saved King Drugo, yes? I hear rumors - they already call you the Hero of Glenumbra. Your arrival is a blessing from the Divines. Will you help me find Ranser's murderer?

King Sebastien would never risk war by slaying King Ranser, but someone wished it to appear he did. As emissary to High King Fahara'jad, it is up to me - and you, my friend - to prove Sebastien's innocence. If not, the Adamant Crown will break.

As you wish. Once you have concluded your business, I urge you to return to me. If we cannot find Ranser's true killer, I fear Shornhelm and Northmoor will plunge into war, and our entire alliance may crumble.

Murdered in the night by an assassin. They found Ranser in his chamber, hacked to pieces. In the resulting chaos, Shornhelm's and Northmoor's delegations fled. There are many who know much, I fear, that are beyond our reach... at least for now.

First, speak to High Priest Canning - he has Ranser's body in the temple near the manse. Canning works to call forth Ranser's spirit, so that we may learn the murderer's identity from the King himself. So far he has had no success. We must learn why.
The Chalice? That beacon of darkness is a foul thing we pried from the dead hands of a daedra-worshipping witch. The world is better off without it. What use does a holy priest have for it?

I shed no tears for Ranser - the dog murdered Ulorion, our Order's founder. Yet I serve the King, and cannot let any accusation against him stand. I'm loathe to trust you numinous gravewalkers, but you may have your beacon - if you prove your worth.

You understand why we are so wary of you demi-mortal numinous. Your very existence conjures thoughts of daedra, or worse. Even so, Oron trusts you, and I see no other way out of our predicament. Take the Chalice to Canning. Clear Sebastien's name.
Oh, you seek the Soulstone of Brall? You, and so many others. You'd shudder to learn what I had to pay to acquire such a rare prize. Why should I give such a valuable treasure to you?

War with Shornhelm would raise the price of steel, but clearing the King's name will keep more of my customers alive. Very well, you may take the stone, on two conditions: first, bring it back. Second, you must earn the right. A favor for a favor.

Of course I will lend you the stone - a bargain is a bargain. A Shornhelm invasion would destroy commerce all over High Rock. For the good of our people, and of our King, I give up to you my dearest treasure. Just be sure I get it back.
The mushrooms grow in the forest to the southwest of Grayborne.
Tell him fear not - I'm quite safe here. The Order is all bluster. They'd not dare threaten us, not in front of all these people. Still, I appreciate your concern. Take care.

Did he? Just between you and me, I've had my share of troubles with the Order. Nothing too bad, mind you, but trouble all the same. During the day, in the crowd, we're safe. Alone, at night... who knows? Tread carefully, friend.

I know Dalomar well - he's down here every day filling our ears with his lies about the Order. Now that you mention it, though, I've not heard any bellyaching recently. Maybe he grew tired of sedition.

You're looking for Dalomar? Well I didn't tell you, but a few days ago there was a Lion Guard bloke down here asking all sorts of questions about him. Funny type. Don't know what came of it, but best you stay clear of whole matter, I think.

I've not seen Dalomar of late - but I did hear something odd. Couple of Lion Guard patrollers were down here yesterday, talking about the fish - how they'd die choking on all their own talk. Had a good laugh about it. Odd, if you ask me.

Begin at the temple by Sebastien's manse. I've heard chatter among the rabble that the undead risings in Northmoor are divine punishment, and the priests have lost Arkay's favor. Fools. If anyone is troubling High Priest Canning, run them off.

Camlorn's tavern, in the lower city. The rabble lose themselves in their cups at the slightest trouble, and a royal assassination is certain to have them uproariously drunk. Make sure the peasants aren't beating in each other's heads.

With our guards drawn to the manse the thieves grow even bolder than before. One rogue even attempted to steal the Chalice of Gwedrun! Go to the docks and reassure the merchants that the Magis Order still watches over them.

That should put you in sufficient sight of any who look to profit from Camlorn's distress. I will patrol as well to see if your appearance has the effect we want. Meet me on Camlorn's docks after you complete your patrol.
Have you not seen the dead walking, friend? Why would Arkay allow such horrors, unless his priests had betrayed him? The Order of Arkay is responsible! They've betrayed us!
The Order! Your pardon - you didn't say you were with the Order. I'm no rabblerouser, I swear it! I'm loyal to the King! I'm just… afraid, is all. I'll go… I'll go. Please don't arrest me.
The Order oversees the graveyard where my father was buried - they said he'd be protected. But now my father is gone. He's among the walking dead!
You may be right, it's just… my father. It was his worst fear. To rise souless, like that… and it's happened. I don't know what to do. I know I shouldn't be here - I'll go home.
Isn't it obvious? Would Arkay allow rampant necromancy? Open your eyes, friend! The Order of Arkay has failed us! The Lord of Coldharbor rules here!

The Order is helping them, you fool! All they do is round up innocent citizens and torture them until they'll admit to anything. Wait… are you with them? You are! You're a fool to keep such company. I'm leaving, don't worry. Keep your lies.
Who do you think you are, walkin' in here? This is Master Jes' house. The stinking Order's not welcome here!
Keep Camlorn calm… well. Fine. I suppose we are causin' a stir. Get on your way then. We'll be good.
Nothin'… two men and too much ale. Forget I said anything. You'll hear no more from us.
Yes. With the artifacts you've gathered, I do believe we have a chance to contact Ranser despite the disturbances beyond the Mundus.

That's good news. If not for the Lion Guard, we'd have to depend on those bloody Hands of Northmoor to protect us. Oh, they're friendly enough if you pay their fees, but try to earn a profit on your own and you're like to be run out of town.

Yes... but we must be cautious. These artifacts glow brightly beyond the Mundus. They will attract more than Ranser's spirit. Any distraction could summon something... unexpected. When you are ready, light the Holy Incense Burner on the left wall.
Yes. We need both artifacts before we can proceed. I'll leave that task to you.
We Bretons don't live as fancy as some folks. Queen Maraya  lets me run the house as I see fit and I keep things simple. I didn't expect that, Her Grace being from across the water and all.
One of the eldest daughters of High King Fahara'jad and as practical as they come. Her Grace keeps to herself mostly, but she's open-handed with gifts come feast days.

I've been the housekeeper since before their wedding, all those years  ago.  Her Grace is pious and pure.  King Sebastien couldn't have brought us a better wife and Queen. Unless he'd married a Breton, that is.
His Grace is strong-minded, like Bretons. Some say His Grace shouldn't have married one of the High King's daughters just to make an easy peace. I say peace isn't always easy, marriage or not.
King Sebastien can be rash... he's always had that regal air. Born to it, you might say.  I will allow that His Grace throws supper across the room less frequently,  now that Queen Maraya's here.

An odd guest. Hardly ate, and drank not a drop of wine. Never wanted any of us in his rooms after he retired, not even his own manservant. If His Departed Highness had let one of us near him, maybe he wouldn't have been sliced to ribbons.
His Grace had odd Shornhelm customs...that is to say...I don't gossip about the dead. It's bad luck!
Murder, that's what! His Highness, King Ranser of Shornhelm. Dead! Benwick ran out of the guest quarters screaming, he did. I daren't go in there.
His Highness's ghost, that's who. He didn't die natural...'twas murder!
Well, I'm sure not touching it! Not alone, anyways. I know they'll make me go in there to scrub up, but I won't go alone. I'm afraid of ghosts!
So much bad news... News enough to turn your stomach. Like cheese will. Do you know what goes into making cheese? Disgusting! I'll never touch the stuff again!

Arkay preserve us! Thrandor Direnni was an Aldmer sorcerer ages ago. Legend has it his sanctum lies somewhere north of here. I will free the possessed - go immediately to the Redoubt north of Camlorn and find Commander Blarae. Recover Ranser's body!
Mother Murk is gonna get you for this!
Troubled times...you know nothing of the werewolves?

The way I heard it, the north is crawling with werewolves! The entire village of Westtry in Dwynnen has been lost to the beasts, and Crosswych is sore beset.  Can't tell friend from foe in them places.
Ah, Thank you. These will work just fine. If you'll just give me a moment, I will grant you your reward.

How you view them depends upon many things. Some say they bring hope to the simple folk who've struggled beneath the Magis Order's dictates. Others say they're little better than bandits. I've never had trouble with them, myself.

You've not heard of them? The Magis Order hunts witches and slays monsters. They were founded to defend Northmoor and they've done a fine job; I've never felt safer.  But some say they go too far. And now, I fear they have too many foes to face.

He said what? That's nonsense! The only reason Vorgo the Red Rook even knows my name is because he's robbed my shipments so many times. nnThe man's a lunatic, and an outlaw besides. Would you take his word over mine?
Yes! Did Geves sent you? I thought I was surely lost!
Thank you. Your efforts today have helped us all.

I don't know. I was bringing tea when I heard shouting. I peeked in the keyhole.nnThere was a shadow by my lord. They were shouting about something - the Shrouded Throne. My lord screamed. I cast open the door, but the room was empty. He was dead!

My lord had mentioned it - only in whispers, when he thought I'd not overhear.nnOh, I shudder to imagine the Shrouded Throne. My lord died when its servant came, and he was the strongest man I knew. If he couldn't stand against it, who could?

My lord's Bloodstone… it was his most treasured possession. I never saw him without it. nnI am so ashamed. I knew they would blame me for my lord's death… I was the last to see him alive! So I took his Bloodstone - to sell, you see - and fled.

No. There was a giant wolf… it attacked us. Poor Bruno. He died for me - he tried to stop the wolf. Then it was upon me!nnWyress Jacinta - bless that woman - fought it off, but the wolf took the stone in its jaws and fled.

Many come and go from Aldcroft every day, or did - before the Order came to town.nnThere is something odd - an emissary to the High King arrived shortly before you did. He's staying upstairs at this very inn. What he wants here I can only guess.
This is not the imposter you are looking for.

King Sebastien rules all of Northmoor, answering only to the High King, Fahara'jad - my master. He was hosting peace talks in Camlorn, with King Ranser of Shornhelm, when the assassin struck, murdering King Ranser in the night.

King Ranser ruled Shornhelm, our neighbor to the north - only recently did we find an uneasy peace. Ranser's death in Camlorn, while under Sebastien's protection, now threatens that peace. With Sebastien suspected, Shornhelm prepares for war.

We have only one lead - a man named Morholdt, who served masters yet unknown. He stole Ranser's body when we tried to raise the fallen king's spirit, to have Ranser reveal his murderer. When we slew him, we discovered Morholdt sought someone here.

One of Ranser's manservants fled Camlorn after his murder. That man is here, in Grayborne. He had a trinket of Ranser's - a Bloodstone. Sadly, Morholdt's allies reached Grayborne ahead of me. The manservant is too wounded to tell me anything.
I'm not missing, I'm perfectly fine! Just need to open this chest of drawers and they won't budge. Can you give me a hand?
He was?nnI see.nnWould you do a bereaved wife a last favor and... retrieve his purse for me?
You haven't heard? Oh, you must be from out of town.
Well, King Ranseur was assassinated last night — right in King Vincintian's manor. They say there was blood all over! And now there's going to be war with Shornhelm!
King Ranseur is lord of Shornhelm. It lies north over the mountains. He was here to join an alliance arranged by our king. Those so-called nobles in Shornhelm  clearly want to stop this.
He is our noble and just ruler. He would never condone such a thing.  Why, there was a score of assassins seen in town! I shudder just thinking about it.
Shornhelm lies to the north. It's a nasty mountainous land and its people are no better. I'm sure they killed their own king just to prevent this alliance. And now they'll try to blame us for it!
That is what I heard. You know the Shornhelm council is sure to use this as an excuse for war. It won't be the first time they've tried - though murdering their own king! How awful.
Well, I just heard it. That's what everybody knows.

You will need to speak with the Princess - a lowly servant such as myself cannot offer you a blessing, even in death. Princess Aurais is just inside the castle. Nothing can touch you while you walk in the spirit world. Be safe.
I am. You do not belong here - you are not one of the Dead. What do you seek?
I have something to show you, then. Please come with me.
If only I had done something in life to deserve such chivalry. You have my blessing, Hero, for what it is worth.
I will return you to your living body, Hero. Good luck.
Excellent! Not many could defeat such a dark foe. I worry, though, that my blessed chains have broken.
What?! That is... very troubling. I must mediate for guidance. In the meantime, ask Ranger Lord Merin if anything needs to be done.
What d'you want?  Suppose those meddling foresters sent you.
You see how it is, then.  Thank you for your mercy.  My wife's just making some stew, if you'll have some.nnGo and talk to her; the least we can do for you is fill your belly.
You'd best watch your back in these woods after today!
So what if it is my arrow?  It's not right all this game should be claimed by fat Daggerfall nobles.nnWhat do I have to feed my empty belly?

She's right to worry. Those soldiers are mad. Did you know one actually took a swing at me? They're so blind. They don't see who they stab.nnI hid a locket in a house to keep those men from getting it. I can't go out now. You'll have to go instead.

The locket! That's it, all right. You're a kind soul, kinder than most, and you've helped me more than I can say. The least we can do is offer you a meal. My wife will insist.nnGo let my wife know I'm on my way home. I'll be right behind you.
Yes, I can help you. However, agents of the infernal lurk at every corner, and I fear for my life. We tread on dangerous ground.

You look like the type who can handle a fight. Take a deputy into the swamp and slay some monsters - just don't dawdle. I want you both back soon - we've got a lot of camp to cover.nnWe'll all be safer by your effort. Tell Rielle when you're done.

I'm so glad to meet you. My sisters and I have done all we can to summon the spirits of the land, but it hasn't been enough.nnThere is one hope. If we can somehow draw the corrupted magic from a lurcher, that might convince the spirits to manifest.

Find a forest lurcher or grove lurcher. Hit it until it breaks. Once broken, use this charm to tame it. nnBring the tamed lurcher here, where our connection with the land is strongest.nnAfter we take it apart, we can examine it more closely.

Pollen, seed, and insect alike are thick with Angof's corruption. nnA flood of corruption flows from the north in a bitter chill, seeking living things and bringing only death.nnI am suffocating on my own breath. Help me, champion.

My veins flow poorly, choked by vines.nnViscous filth obscures my blind eyes.nnMy streams are thick with muck. Fish and moss alike both die.nnAngof sends pollution from ancient graves of Cath Bedraud, north of here. Go there. Stop him.

My body is rife with seeds of corruption sprouting tendrils of hate.nnFoulness seeps into the trees, the animals, even the rocks. nnAncient, powerful nature magic from the north carries the foul stench of necromancy.nnAngof. Stop Angof.

Wraiths in the ruins east of Camlorn attacked a merchant named Jael. Now you'll see how we turn evil against evil.nnWe took this Soul Cage from a necromancer. Go to the ruins.Fight the wraiths until they are weak, then use the Soul Cage to trap them.
The Chalice of Gwedrun. Dark times lead to dark measures.

It's the Chalice of Gwedrun you want? No one in Camlorn can be trusted, and I'll not part with it easily. Prove yourself to me by helping the Lion Guard with their patrols or by clearing the ruins of some troublesome wraiths, and I'll consider it.
Indeed you have. Very well, the Chalice of Gwedrun is yours.
Indeed you have. Very well, the Chalice of Gwedrun is yours.

Coty! So loyal. Always at my side. nnHow many battles have we seen, you and I? How often have we survived, when others fell? nnDivines willing, today we'll see the destruction of the Alessian Order. Slay them all, my friend! For king and kingdom!

I know. I forged it for Coty Danain. nnI sent him on a quest to kill a dangerous enemy of the Direnni Hegemony, an Altmer werewolf named Faolchu.nnCoty will prevail in this realm, but that won't help you in yours. What happened?

Yes. All things forged by my magic retain a tie to me.nnI can sense a trace of where the sword will be. I sense an echo of its future... and yours.nnReturn to your time. Ask Coty's spirit about the Cave of Penance. There, you will find your thief.

You bring with you a trace of your origins: the broken strings of the veil of time.nnI can sense the trials that await you. The dead will walk. The planes will meld.nnI can tell that your thief was here. He is no longer. It is time for you to go.

This arrow?  I've mended arrows like these for Felix Glenan, and his band of trappers.  Their camp is to the northwest, up the hill.nnSome poach because it's the only way to survive, these days.  Still, the law's the law.  I stay out of it.

These belong to Felix Glenan and his band of trappers.  They're in that camp there, just to the north.nnSome poach because it's the only way to survive, these days.  Still, the law's the law.  I stay out of it.

Valyn, a Dreadlord lies within. nnWhat is a dreadlord you ask? A fallen god as the wives tales would put it. We do not know if this is true, but if they wish to pull him into this realm to use as their own.nnWe cannot let this happen.

I only wish it were a fairy tale.nnColdun wishes to pull a dreadlord from the Veil for its own use. A fallen god, some would say. Not only will it destroy this region if they succeed, no mortal can hope to hurt the demon if brought under control.

Tch.  No easy answer there.  Daggerfall  nobles claim the deer for themselves.  There's plenty of other game, most of the time.nnThese days, though, a trapper might take whatever he can get, with the forests as dangerous as they are.

Daggerfall  nobles claim the deer for themselves.  There's plenty of other game, most of the time.nnThese days, though, a trapper might take whatever he can get, with the forests as dangerous as they are.  A man might need to poach just to get by.

You may not be as dumb witted as I first thought.nnWe can only hold the gate to the spirit realm open for a limited time. If you do not return in that short period, your spirit is as damned as those who wander that realm.

I seek Dwemer relics from the distant past... relics integral to deciphering the Deep Folk.nnOnce I uncover them, the Mages Guild will have no choice but to invite me into their order!nnIf they want access to them, they'll have no choice.
So you've dispensed with Corbeau, have you? If only that were the end of our troubles with the Rooks. They're a plague on Camlorn, and a plague on my name.

The sad thing is, Uncle Forton was killed by those trees not long ago. You know, his strongbox is still out there in the woods.nnWe won't brave those spriggans, but if you went and found it, we wouldn't grudge you keeping whatever was inside.

Friend, I can see how a sack lying in a boat might seem like something you can just come by and take.nnI must impress upon you that most valuable items, such as the heirloom within that sack, are owned.nnI own the heirloom in question. Give it back.
A wise move. My thanks, friend. nnWhy don't you go speak to old Warden Moreau? nnHe might give you something in compensation, now that you've wisely decided not to interfere with our plan.
You obviously know it isn't. That's beside the point. nnSo, friend, I recommend you give that back to me, as I am its most recent owner.
You're going to regret that decision. nnYou're going to regret it very soon... and very badly.

Oh, yes. That ring belongs to Warden Thierry. It was his father's ring, if I'm not mistaken. nnHe would be very happy if you returned it to him. He's posted just outside Deleyn's Mill on the road to Daggerfall.
No. I'm sorry, but that ring doesn't look familiar to me.
Stendarr! You found my ring. This is more valuable than you can imagine, friend. I believe I might even have something for you...
This... this is my family ring. It belongs to my brother. He will be elated to receive it. Please, take this to him. He is right over there guarding the camp. You have my thanks!
As I suspected. This Thorn reeks of Angof's Reach Magic. Angof! How dare he meddle in my swamp?nnStill, knowing our enemy will allow me to reduce his influence in my kingdom, at least.

Angof is a Witchman of the Reach. A grave singer...you would consider him a necromancer, perhaps. Someone who corrupts the natural order of the world.nnAs such, he was sent away from the Reach. I do not know what is in his mind now.
All these refugees. I feel for them, and I know they need a home, but it can't be here. There isn't any room and the place smells of waste.
It's horrible what's happened there. I'm glad the Lion Guard is here to help take Camlorn back.
Werewolves took over the city is what I hear . Some say there's a big werewolf leader, uglier than most. He's what turned most of the people into werewolves.
I want to go home. Here, I'm living in my own filth. This harbor cannot support the number of people here. Duke Sebastien needs to do something to get us home.
We've all lost family in the worst way possible. I saw my own husband, he...he killed my mother when he turned into that - that damned thing.
Yes. A werewolf. That's how they do it. Take us one at a time and turn us into wolves. They make us fight for them...and do worse.
Duke Sebastien called for help from High King Geriant and His Majesty's sent Averos and his Lion Guard. I hope Averos can take our homes back from those werewolves.
They sent us here to take her back. That's as plain a mission as you could want. What they didn't tell us before we came over the Iliac Bay is that she's been taken by werewolves.
Overrun by werewolves, or overrun by men, we'll take her back. The only difference between fur and skin is they smell different when they burn.
Sibellec? I hear that her precious moors aren't hers anymore. Whatever has been happening to High Rock hasn't left her alone either.
Sibellec is the 'queen of the moors'. We've pretty much left her alone and she's left us alone.
Some people claim she came here from the Reach. I won't speak of her anymore here - her ears are everywhere!
If you ask me, Sibellec is the cause of all these troubles. That witch wants one thing: for us to be gone.
Sibellec means us no harm. She's an odd one to be sure, but she just wants to be left alone.
I don't know anything about her. Sorry.
I don't know anything about her. Sorry.
Sibellec, I don't know for sure, but supposedly Duke Sebastien is trying to get her aid in dealing with the problems in the moor so we don't have to fight a battle on two fronts.
If you tell this to anyone else I'll call you a liar, but Sibellec once cured a disease I'd gotten from a...very friendly barmaid. Sibellec is strange, but you can trust her.
Just some local witch, right? I can't say I know much about her.
Duke Sebastien and Lord Averos have cooked up some plan to use her to keep the creatures off of us while we kill wolves.
No, I've not heard that name.
Angof... yes. I think I overheard a guard mention it. They lay the troubles of the land at his feet. They say he is from the Reach.
Angof. I hear he's an agent of the Aldmeri Dominion. They call him the Master of Thorns.
Angof, no. I don't know the name.
Angof... no. The only name I know or care about is that wolf... Faolchu. I won't get a good night's rest until he is burned and his ashes scattered over the Iliac Bay.
Angof, the Master of Thorns. Yes, he's taken up in old Cath Bedraud. At least, that's what I hear.
Angof is our next stop after we liberate Camlorn. We've already got a camp near his hold out in Cath Bedraud.
They say he's got a hold on some big cemetery in the North.
One of the refugees claims it's him what leads the wolves.
The pack leader. He's responsible for the death of Camlorn. The spit dries in my mouth just saying his name.
Damned, he is. The talk is he's a foul legend come back to life. Not like any other werewolf I've heard of, and his pack isn't afraid of the sun.
Aye, that name I know well enough. He's foul, that one is. Stinks of the grave and smells of mange. I've an arrow I'd like to test on him.
He's the pack leader. Made all the other werewolves around. Kill him and we've got a chance.
He's the pack leader. Made all the other wolves around. Kill him, and we've got a chance.
He's working for Angof. Apparently Angof raised him from the grave. Our job is to put him back there.

Have you now? You betray us, and now you hope to do the same for your new master? nnYou have already shown your true colors in this fight. We have no use for traitors.nnDo what your brutish master tells you. Leave us be.

I've done a lot of traveling in my youth. Seen all sorts of wild creatures.nnBut that is a story for another place and time. This is not something that should concern you. You've done your job well and I suspect the Elder waits eagerly for you.

That I did. nnThese spiders carry a poison that I've seen kill large animals in seconds. You seem to be fine however, otherwise you'd be strewn about the corpses.nnWhat concerns me, is why they are here. This is not their region of habitat.

I apologize if I implied that you couldn't handle your weapon. You proved your skills surely enough by the corpses at your feet. nnThese spiders though, they are not of this region. I am still unsure why they are here and where they came from.

Coldun is a dark place now, dishonoring its former glory as a nation of peace and prosperity. Their leaders, they practice dark magics that no man should trifle with. Magic of death. Necromancy.nnI'm afraid Camaroot is not all that they seek.

The Bloody Eye are one. Already I have sent a messanger ahead to their leader and my friend, Sly Sheldon.nnThey are a group of... mystics, if you will. If anyone knows what other purposes the Coldun army have to march upon Alaygon, it would be them.

Nay, I dare say we have enough time to get message to one.nnYou must make haste. The hourglass sands are quickly falling and I fear what shall happen when they are all but gone. All of these lands must be ready.

The nomads in the forests to the north. They are... different then what you might expect, but harmless I assure you. They must be warned at once of the approaching army. I fear Coldun will simply rip right through them if they serve no need.
Indeed you are. I can mend your soul from its journey to Cold Harbor, if you wish.
Arkay's blessing has been granted. The corruption of the unclean has been cleansed from your soul.
I can restore you to your body in Mundus, but there is a cost. Your body must be moved to the Wayshrine, and this will damage it. The damage will heal only with time.
Well I can send you back to the real world, but you'll be sick for 10 minutes and it can't be cured.
A pity, but there are many more young soldiers here who could use your aid. Would you like to try again?
May your hunt fare better this time, Numinous.

The sheets! The confounded sheets!nnYes, there's a band of miscreant looters down at the docks. Pirates, or their allies, I expect.nnNo doubt they're hiding the sheets there somewhere, hoping to sell them later. Astrid's Lot, they're called.
As you wish. Divines protect you.
Very well. Faolchu started this nightmare.nnDivines willing, you'll end it.

That buffon Chancellor Weller certainly has been complaining about this or that. You might try to see what has been causing the clouds to swallow his sunshine. He's in the fancy blue tents in the northeast part of the port.
Warden Rielle over at the guard tower in the southern part of the port seems to be worried about her volunteers. She's working with a bunch of raw kids trying to play at soldiering.
Lord Averos has been trying to take the war to the werewolves ever since he arrived from Wayrest. I know he's at the port's Northwestern gate looking for help on how best to take back Camlorn.
Rolantae? We have not spoken in many years....
Ah. She still knows me well.nnI do possess such an item. I have kept this box for many years. Open it on the ship - you shall have your distraction.
Egads! Your prowess is unmatched, indubitably. Let me take those, and hearten our soldiers with the raiments of our slain enemies.
Ahnarra grieves for Camlorn. Overrun by werewolves, its citizens forced to live in filth here in Aldcroft. Once Duke Sebastien cleanses Camlorn, Ahnarra will be glad to return there.
That is a difficult name for Ahnarra. Sib...Sib...how do you say it? All Ahnarra knows is that this person lives in the swamps.
That is a name Ahnarra does not speak aloud. It is too dangerous.
Ahnarra heard that Faolchu's bite is worse than his bark.
Let's go, then.  Beware of lights over the water!

Lost in the realm in which we refer to as the Veil. nIt is here the Bloody Eye watches over. We have all gone through trials in order to tune ourselves to pass into this world. To keep watch to those who would disturb the spirits who dwell there.

Yes.nnThey practice the art of death magic, necromancy. With their hands, they dip into the murky depths of the Veil, hoping to use the damned spirits as their own. nnTo this end, they must be stopped.

You may not be as dumb witted as I first thought.nnIn order for the ritual to be a success, a sacrifice must be made to appease the demon. This sacrifice will come from the blood of the villagers of Alaygon.nnScared yet, hero?

You must destroy the statues scattered about the town. nnWe can only hold the gate to the spirit realm open for a limited time. If you do not return in that short period, your spirit is as damned as those who are lost within the Veil.
Fine, but please... make your case brief.
...then I choose to join my soul with Aldmeris.

This is sad. I can't condone his actions, but he has risked his life for this community more than once. I leave this up to you. If you wish to turn him in, speak to Captain Rielle near the little house to the North.

The flagship has ridden at anchor for days now. This has allowed me to make detailed observations of its position. I believe I can teleport you aboard.nnYou will merely have to fight through the crew and kill the Commander.

You need wolfsbane? Did Muriel send you? That old Breton cure for werewolves was never proven.nnWhat you really need is bee's... no, worm's... no, no....nnAh! Foxglove nectar! Foxglove with silver! That purges the poisons very quickly.

Wolfsbane grows on the western side of most trees near the camp.nnIt's not a proven cure, but I'm sure Muriel can something with it if you take enough of it to her.nnIf you gather foxglove nectar instead, bring it to me.

Foxgloves grow on the eastern side of most trees near the camp. You can get fleas from them... I mean, nectar.nnBring the nectar to me and I'll mix it up with grubs... er, silver.nnIf you'd rather get wolfsbane, take it to Muriel. I can't stand it.

I just combine the wolfsbane with this potion of liquid silver. There you go!nnMy grandmother taught me these remedies, though they've fallen from favor lately. Would you mind administering this to one of the soldiers in the tent for me?
She would understand that an individual has the right to choose if they live or die. She would respect my wishes.
Do not jest at a time like this.
Yes... yes, that may be the best idea. Thank you for your insight.
Well, no... of course not. I didn't think....

Good choice! Anemone Nectar is always used in...oh, wait. This is Foxglove Nectar. That's what I meant. Foxglove speeds up the healing process.nnI've added it to this vial of Liquid Silver. This'll work on the wounded soldiers; try it!
Prepare yourself. I cannot account for the motion of waves!

You could ask other Numinous, I suppose. But... perhaps there is another way.nnTalrien the Archivist possesses a singular item which may aid you. Seek him in the depths of the Umbral Tower, which lies in the bay to the east.
Well that is a bit trickier, isn't it? There is one possibility, though...

I just combine the Wolfsbane with this potion of Liquid Silver....and there you go!nnMy grandmother taught me these remedies, though they've fallen from favor lately. Would you mind administering this to one of the soldiers in the tent for me?
Then let us summon the beast.

Do not thank me yet. Alaygon still faces grave danger in the coming hours.nnYou have my assistance. I have already sent word ahead for the rest to meet you in town. Speak to Scag as soon as possible.nnI wish you luck, child of man.

I will protect the villagers from the dark magics so that they can not be turned, however you must still protect their fragile lives.nnTamarus has already gathered a small force together to fend off the coming attack. I shall send the nomads as well.

At first we did not know. All we could tell was that some illness had struck him down, put him on his death bed.nnBut a shadow of doubt clouded my mind. Why had the King fell ill when no others who served him showed no signs?

Poison, fed to him by his own son.nnHe was tainted with the dark magics, his associations bringing his soul away, far from saving.nnHe killed his father to ascend the throne.. and soon the chaos started.

Civil war erupted in the kingdom. The prince, now king, struck at our allies with his armies when they least expected it. Quickly they fell to his might and power.nnI barely escaped with my life. I refused to take part in the.. madness that occured.
I fled, like a coward. nnI supposed life in the western lands would be safe.. but it has caught up to me now.nnThe King of Coldun will want my head.. but we will strike first.

You have done much already, my friend, but it would be an honor.nnRest now, you have helped save this village and there is still much to be done. nnIn the morning I will gather the villagers..nnToday, victory is ours!
We will attack Coldun from within.nnI will gather a small band and travel far east to see why Coldun marches forth. nnWhen we know the cause.. we will stop them.
Oh, you stay clear of Astrid's Nords, youngster.  They're nothing but trouble, came here about the same time as the Camlorn refugees and been trouble ever since.
The Pallid Devils have seized our island of Sunhold, from which they operate siege weapons both arcane and mundane. It is an inconvenient situation.
You must see the madness if you insist then.nnIf you wish to save Alaygon and stop Coldun, you must get a taste of what the Veil holds.

First, we must make sure you will survive the trip into the Veil. nnPlease, close your eyes. I will send you into the spirit realm for but a moment's time. We need to see if your mind will maintain a balance to survive. nnGood luck.
Very well. Be sure to place the crown fragment as soon as I tell you to.

When Karnosis channeled the power from the Doomcrag, we all became a part of it, including Karnosis, <<1>>, <<2>>, and me.nnWe feel the weight on our souls. We suffer from unending thirst. We're weakened when drawn away from a source of that power.

Damned witches I'd say. We keep an open trade in town with them, mainly because Tamarus vouches for them.nnThey've never harmed us, and they keep to their selves in the mountains, but they claim they can speak to the dead!nnI say keep them away!
Nomads? In the woods?nnWe tend to stay away from the forests. Strange things happen there. I suppose something could live there... but I wouldn't know. I don't get out much that way.

Not much I'm afraid.nnTamarus hails from there, but he's been with this village for years now as our smith and he is a good man. The contrast in manner between that soldier and Tamarus is astonishing to be honest.nnOther than that.. I know nothing.

<<1>> will use the power of fire to destroy you.nnTo tame it, I'll attempt to summon healing waters you can use in the fight.nnBe warned, though. If <<1>> summons his wraith, you'll need to avoid him at all costs.

Only what Tamarus has told me.nnHe lived there for a many years, but says the kingdom collapsed under a great shadow of its former glory.nnThe rulers of that land practice the dark arts. They rule by fear and power over their people.

They practice magic that causes fear in those whom have no knowledge of its purpose. nnSly is a friend to this village, even if many are not a friend to him. He keeps his group in the mountains, away from it all not to cause a stir.

Ahh yes. nn<The woman chuckles, but her face draws grim a moment later>nnThey.. they would not harm anyone. I fear for what Coldun will do to them if they find them in the forests. Will they force them to join us as well in their... army?
Yes?  Is there something I can do for you?
Are you now? Tell me then, my dear, convenient Numinous - would you be willing to participate in a thrilling investigation of larceny and deceit?

Magnificent!nnI have crafted a Magicka Pulsator! When used, the device will reveal magicka residue left behind by heavily enchanted items such as a Varla Lens. nnThe trail starts on the beach. Follow it to pursue that wretched thief.

I feel no anger towards him. Long ago he was my mentor. All I know of tending the Varlines comes of his wisdom.nnI do not know why he sought to create an Imago Serry by turning living people to stone. I only know that I... regret his passing.
I'm sure he keeps it in his retreat, somewhere near the foothills north of here. But take care - He won't like anyone invading his space. I fear he's gone quite mad.

Upon use, you will see the residual trail of magicka left behind by the Varla Lens. nnNow consider this: the Lens fell onto the beach. That is where the Maormer thief lay in wait for it, so that is where the trail would logically start.

Come to visit Mother Murk, have you?nnOnce the people of Crosswych brought me tributes. They feared and respected me.nnNow only my good children tend to their kindly mother.  We watch the rest. We wait.nnSoon, the bad children will be punished!
You killed a Kirin? The creature that embodies all that is beautiful, magical, and elegant...?
You managed to slay a Giant Sea Serpent?n...A brave choice, Optimate. Give me a moment and your enchanted item will be complete.
You see before you an image of M'Kraka. This one is amused by your intrusion, and will humor it.
I did find a book on the bridge, Optimate. I shall fetch it for you.

Arnand? He gave us a hard time back in training. Made us the soldiers we are today. Good man. nnI won't ask how you know about the talisman. I'll just thank you for bringing it.nnLook for Marcel Wirich at an altar to the west. He'll know how to help.
Yes, yes. This will do nicely. nnI should be able to discover what's causing the poor people dying in the mine to fall under Angof's influence...nn...but first, I have something for you.

Previously, I theorized that Welkynd Stones have power over the undead. nnUnfortunately, my theories were too controversial for most scholars. My research has proven to be extremely difficult. nnThat's why my discoveries here are so important!

While exploring the ruins, we pushed through into a chamber containing Welkynd Stones. nnIt was late, so I picked up a single stone and returned to camp.nnThat night, spectres and zombies attacked me relentlessly! I barely escaped to Crosswych.

I know! I must conduct further experiments, but I fear for my life. nnIf we can prove the link between Welkynd Stones and the undead, I will finally be vindicated.nnWe might even find a new method of defeating the undead!

Why?nnBecause you, my friend, are trapped like the rest of us. Do you not think Coldun watches the path on both sides of the mountains? You could attempt to flee, but they will make sure no one leaves this village.nnThat is why.

The talisman once had immense power. It opened portals to other realms.nnSome say a Daedric Prince made it. Others claim a Telvanni mage conjured it.nnNo matter what its origin, Ulorion knew it was far too powerful to be in Tamriel.

The Magis Order couldn't break the talisman. It could only be... changed.nnUlorion found a confluence: a place where air, water, and earth were in balance. There, he asked the spirits of the land for help. He asked them to weaken the talisman.

The spirits hid the Midnight Talisman's power away.n nTo keep the talisman safe, we only tell this story to a few heroes in the Lion Guard.nnI only know it because I heard it from my teacher, who heard it from Ulorion himself.

The last stranger we trusted was false, a thrall of the Spirit Daedra.nnYou are different. The words on your breath feel true. We believe you want to defeat Angof... but can you?nnShow us the power you possess. Defeat my champion to gain my blessing.

Your blood flows with purpose, and your eyes reflect truth. nnYou are brave, and you have power, but I wonder...  would you truly sacrifice yourself to save us all?nnShow your bravery. Prove your selflessness. Face my champion to gain my blessing.

I nourish life, yet all return to me in time.n nYour connection to life is tenuous.  Do you understand the urgent desire to live?nnThis desire infuses all who live. You must feel it if you wish to defeat Angof. Face my champion to gain my blessing.

The spirits didn't bless the talisman. They blessed you. nnOnly you can wield the Midnight Talisman. To anyone else, it's useless.nnThe spirits wouldn't entrust such power lightly. You are the only one who can defeat Angof.

I believe you. Take the talisman with my blessing, along with our blessings. I have faith in our cause. I know you won't fail us.nnGo tell Magus Commander Panoit that we're ready for our final attack.nnYour triumph awaits you.
Vilmo sent you! He would have me stand by and watch the Orrery decay. I will not! The Orrery must fall, for only through its destruction can it be reborn.nnDo you not agree?
What a terrible tragedy.nnS'Raverr and his daughter had just moved here. The mine collapsed. Many died.  nnAnd now?  Now it's worse.

It was Dwynarth, you know, an ancient Alyeid city.  Scholars come from time to time, to study them; I think there's some up there now.  They say you could go there sometimes and speak to those who have passed on, but it's probably just stories.
The Maormer are not without some skills of note. Their master shipwrights designed a vessel with the ability to pass through land as if it were ocean.
At the far northern end of the Stonewake.nnIf you visit, be wary. The Landbreaker's passage stirred many dangers.
They sought to destroy our blessed Crystal Tower. Arrogance clouded their judgement.nnThee Tower's mages prevented the ship from reaching its target.
Those children... now that's a strange thing.  Running into the woods at all hours, acting strangely, even aggressively!  Each parent swears it's not their own child, but who knows...
I don't know about them running off, but one of those wee miscreants broke into my forge and stole tools and wrecked the place.  The children in this town act like none should, I tell you.
It is likely. There are musical instruments scattered throughout the cave. Play a hymn to Mara upon any of them, and the Nereids shall know you as a friend.
<This pedestal resonates with a dull hum.>
<The resulting cacophony knocks the resonance crystal from the pillar.>
<The tone of the crystal and the hum of the pillar harmonize into a euphonious chord.>nn<You feel tranquility resonating through you.>
<The resulting cacophony knocks the resonance crystal from the pillar.>
<This pedestal resonates with a high-pitched hum.>
<The resulting cacophony knocks the resonance crystal from the pillar.>
<The resulting cacophony knocks the resonance crystal from the pillar.>
<The tone of the crystal and the hum of the pillar harmonize to create a euphonious chord.>nn<You feel tranquility resonate through out your body.>
That is most gracious. The Bell is stored within a cave, hidden behind one of the Fane's waterfalls. It is under the protection of the Liriel Nereids.
<This pedestal gives off a low hum.>
<The tone of the crystal and the hum of the pillar harmonize into a euphonious chord.>nn<You feel tranquility resonate through your body.>
<The resulting cacophony knocks the resonance crystal from the pillar.>
<The resulting cacophony knocks the resonance crystal from the pillar.>
There are musical instruments scattered throughout the cave. Play a hymn to Mara upon any of them, and the Nereids shall know you as a friend.
The writing is barely legible. She writes of seeing outside the Aetherius? These symbols...
The tone of the crystal and the hum of the pillar combine to create a resonance that sends calm through out your body.

<<1>> is just defending her own. Al'kari keeps chickens. Chickens love <<1>>.nnGulitte keeps rats. Rats hate <<1>>'s chickens, so he and <<1>> fight!nnWant to help? Catnip can lure a cat to Gulitte's house. It can eat his rats! Save <<1>>'s chickens!

<<1>>'s obsessed with chickens. Am I wrong to ask she keep them out of my yard?nnI keep rats. <<1>>'s  chickens upset my rats greatly!nnWant to settle this? Get some catnip to lure a cat to <<1>>'s house. Let it chase away her chickens!
Al'kari thanks you! Al'kari's children thank you as well.nnYou are a true friend to Khajiit and Khajiit brethen. Al'kari's chickens will one day sing your name.
Well done, my friend. Those Khajiit seem to have no sense of common decency.nnYou did the right thing. Al'kari can channel her energies into something that won't bother my rats.
That cave-in... so many lives lost....nnNow few will go there, out of fear. They say the mines are haunted.  nnCrosswych needs that mine, though. We have few other sources of income here.
The Ironstone Mines are cursed! Everyone here knows that. nnThey say it's because of something the miners found there, just before the attack of the risen dead.

First, there was the cave-in. Now the mines are filled with undead. nnWithout the Ironstone Mines, there would be no Crosswych, but it's been a curse as much as it's been a blessing.nnActually, it's been more of a curse lately.

The ruins? Dwynnarth was an ancient Alyeid city.nnScholars show up from time to time to study them. I think there's a few up there now.nnSome say you can go there and talk to the shades of the departed. That's probably just a story.
Those old ruins? No one goes there anymore.nnWe have enough trouble with the mines without looking for more of it.nnIt's not worth looking at a pile of haunted old stones.

I think there's a scholar up there now, probably studying the stones. Most of us Crosswych folk stay away. nnThey say there's some sort of magical power source there, but like everything else around here, it's wretched haunted.

Something's responsible for all this.nnThey're running into the woods at all hours, acting strangely, and lashing out like little beasts! nnEach mother swears her child is fine. The fathers just get angry. No one wants to take responsibility.

Children in Crosswych are a menace! I've never seen anything like it. nnSimple child's mischief is one thing, but those wicked little scamps cause more trouble than you could possibly imagine.nnIt's disgraceful!

My own children are well-behaved, but some of the others here... well, their behavior would shock you!nn Aggressive, mean, and reckless. You know what? I want to know who their parents are! I blame them.

It's the high cemetery for all the Bretons... or it was, at least.nnNow it's just the unholy pit these foul undead crawl from.  nnThe Lion Guard soldiers are doing all they can there. Can you imagine fighting the risen bones of your own kin?

Cath Bedraud? Bretons have been buried there for centuries. Even their kings and queens are interred there.nnOnce, it was a beautiful place, but now you can't go anywhere near it. It's too dangerous. nnIf I were you, I wouldn't go there.

Once it was a beautiful landmark, something Bretons could be proud of.nnNow it's just like everything else here: ruined and overrun with undead horrors.nnIt's the high cemetery, you know! Very impressive.
He's blighted Glenumbra.nnIf the Magis Order could ever defeat that vile dog, perhaps we could go back to a life without undead horrors.nnI doubt that would ever happen. We'll never be rid of him.
Don't even speak that name! nnWe've suffered enough because of him. For all I know, that evil wizard is watching us right now!nnHe's poisoning Glenumbra. No one knows what he has planned fo us.
Only this: he must be stopped.nnI don't know whether it's going to take a few brave souls or an entire army.nnEither way, we can't endure his evil any longer.

That place was once the home of my distant ancestors. nnYou'll see Ayleid stones there. They're superior to any other magic you'll find.nnOh, and a scholar named Lael  was here a few days ago. She was headed in that direction. I sold her some paper.
I met a scholar who was headed out to the ruins.nnShe bought a pony from me. She needed it to carry all her books.nnThat's a dangerous place to study!
S'Raverr knows very little about them.nnPerhaps Theldyn Andalor would know?nnYes. Ask her! This one does not know much.
I've only seen them once. They're not very impressive.  nnFolks only care about them because they're haunted.

Ah, the ancient Ayleid site! nnThat scholar, what was her name? Lael! That's her.nnShe wanted us to fend off the undead while she did her research. Imagine that!nnWe have orders. We defend the town. As it is, we have our hands full! She's on her own.

We used to play among the stones there when I was a little girl!nnWe can't now, though. It's too dangerous, even if you travel in numbers.nnIt's never safe there, even if you're armed. You should stay away from that place.
We used to play among the stones when I was a little girl.  Not now, though - it's dangerous even if you're in numbers and armed.
The mines? Rabinna would never go there. It's much too dangerous.nnThis one fears for the safety of the miners.
My wife was in the mines when they collapsed last year. She was lucky to get out alive! nnNow she works in the village with me.nnThat place is cursed. I won't let her go back.

My sister will be working there soon.nnI fear for her safety, what with all the undead and the cave-ins. Still, it's a good living, if you can survive it.  nnWe'll ask the Eight for their blessing and hope for the best.
My brother doesn't want me to go in the mines.nnFirst, there was the collapse. Now they say it's haunted. nnYou know what? I'm not afraid. They don't scare me.
I was one of the lucky ones. That's all I'll say.  nnIt's folly to go in there again, but a man has to feed his family somehow.nn We do what we must.

These Bretons are fearful of the mines, but how bad can it be? nnI spent seven years cutting rock in the Alik'r Desert! I had scorpions in my boots and sand sharks breathing down my neck.nnIf there's good money to be made here, I'll take my chances.

That place is crawling with undead. nnThey're just like those wretches who murdered my father at Cath Bedraud last month.nnI'd go there and wreak some havoc... if I didn't have orders from Averos himself to defend the town.
I was deployed here after the cave-in last year.nnI'll tell you this much: it's an evil place.
There was a cave-in there last year, during the Second Seed.  nnMany miners perished. Now the place is thick with undead.nnI don't want to see their faces again.

I don't know much about that mine, except there are plenty of undead to fight.  nnThe people here say it's cursed. I don't know if that's true.nnThe place is full of walking dead. That's bad enough for me.
Children. What a delight! nnS'Raverr has seven of his own. This one's daughter, Rabinna, helps S'Raverr here. nnBe careful of these Crosswych children, my friend. They're not... quite... right.
Rabinna would like to have children someday, but not if they resemble those Crosswych terrors. nnThey're wicked little things!
The children in this village are a menace!nnI think it was Panoit's boy who broke into my forge and stole my tools.nnHe says it wasn't, of course, but they're lying little thieves!
One of the girls here was trying to herd all of our goats.nnTurns out, she was trying to send them off into the marshes. nnIt's strange how the children around here act, sometimes....
I caught one of those little wretches sneaking into our supplies the other night.nnHe ran away before I could get my hands on him! He has no idea how lucky he was....
I've seen them running through these gates and into the forest at all hours of the night.nnWhat parent could let their child do that? nnI know who's really to blame. It's the parents!

Breton children are always unmanageable.nnRirne says it's just the Crosswych children, but I can't stand any of them.nnDon't get me wrong. It's nothing personal. I just know all Breton children are the same, everywhere you go.nnThey're all brats.
Everyone complains about the children.nnWhat can we do?  We're soldiers, not nannies.
I've seen children run through these gates and out into the forest at all hours of the night.  nnCan you believe it? What kind of parent lets their children do that?

The great cemetery?nnS'Raverr has never been there, but this one knows that's where the Bretons keep their dead.nnThere must be hundreds of thousands of Bretons in that cemetery. Even the most exalted kings are buried there!nnRemarkable, isn't it?
Rabinna doesn't know much about the cemetary, only that it's of great importance to the Bretons here.nnThis one is not an archaeologist. This one does not understand.

Cath Bedraud! Now that's a cursed place, if ever I knew one.nnOur order needs all the help it can get there. I took a wagonload of weapons to them a fortnight ago.nnI sincerely hope they're not all dead by now. One would hope.

My father was slain there. My sister and I both joined the Magis Order the next day.nnWe made a vow. We'll cut down every monstrosity that arises from that foul place.nnWe won't stop until our father is avenged.
If there's an evil heart hidden in this land, it beats somewhere in there.
Angof. Yes. Of course. nnThey say... they say he is the cause of so much trouble here.nnThey say horrible, evil things about him!nnForget about that for now. Have some wine.
He has brought great misery to many.nnSomeone should cause him some misery!nnThat would be justice. Someone should make him miserable.

My uncle is a forester. He works in the southern woods. nnHave you seen what Angof has wrought there?  Do you know of the evil that came to those woods?nnHe's twisted the land. He's poisoned it. Now his legion of bones threatens everything we have.
There are those here who won't even speak his name out loud.nnThey're afraid he'll hear them.nnI'll say no more about the matter.

They say he listens through the briars.nnThey say his evil seeps under every rock and into every shadow. His curse is spreading, reaching to the farthest corners of Glenumbra!nnSomething must be done before it's... too late!nnThat's what they say.

They call him the Master of Thorns! They say he's the Grave Singer! nnMe? I just call him "Evil Bastard Waiting to Get His Head on My Pike." nnWhat do you think of that name? Is that good enough?nnMy poetic talents are wasted as a soldier.

Our troops marched through Wrothgar on our way here. I saw his handiwork as we passed Cath Bedraud.nnHe has no tactics or strategy. He wants to poison everything here, scheming until all of Glenumbra has been corrupted.nnThat seems to be working.

Angof? That's the one villain I'd like to kill more than any of my other enemies. nnCut off the head, and shortly thereafter, the head will die.nnThey should let me at him. I'd solve all this with one swift stroke.

Skorvild the Smithy says my boy Etienne broke into his forge. nnHe claims my boy stole his tools and wrecked the place. I know it wasn't him. He's a good boy!nnI saw the footprints, though. It was someone's child... but whose?
Cold Harbor is a plane of Oblivion ruled by Molag Bal, a Daedric prince of great power. nnI do not know why souls of your kind travel to Cold Harbor, but I believe Molag Bal is involved.
When you or one like you is killed, your soul travels to Cold Harbor. The gateway back is the place where your soul departed its body. Coming back through this gateway has a cost to your soul.

Yes, Cold Harbor diminishes your soul. At first, there are minimal noticeable effects. After repeated deaths, however, and without the healing I provide, your weakened soul will affect your body and mind.

I cannot heal this sickness. Your body and soul were rejoined at the Wayshrine. Your body was moved to the Wayshrine through magic. This always takes a toll on your body, but the sickness will heal over time.
Magnus? I believe the common thought about him from Mundus is that he is the wellspring of what you would call magic. He is et'Ada, and has long since abandoned Mundus.

The Mundus is a plane apart and yet surrounded by Oblivion. It was architected by Magnus from the vision of Lorkhan. It is where you were born and where you live this incarnation of your life, Numinous.
Lorkhan was the trickster. He lied to get others of his kind to create Mundus. He succeeded of course, but not without paying a price. But I know little enough of such things.
Follow me. I'll take you to her.
Follow me, I will take you to her.

A few days back, we left Daggerfall to aid Camlorn. nnWhen we stopped to resupply at Farwatch Tower, the Altmer ambushed us. They came out of nowhere!nnNow they've got the tower. We can't let them hold it, but Camlorn still needs our help.
Light that signal fire!nnDaggerfall will send more troops. Then we can keep marching to Camlorn. nnWhen we get there, we'll join forces with the Lion Guard and retake the city.

Casimir got word that the city fell.nnApparently, there's an army of werewolves there. I heard they were once the citizens of Camlorn. nnWe can't help them because we're stuck here. We're busy fighting the Altmer, but you can turn the tide of battle.
That's up to you. If you try to assault the tower, you might want to follow one of my assault teams over. But, if you have enough seasoned vets, you can assault it without waiting for my team.

I presume he wasn't dead when you arrived? Good show. nnYes, this is serious. The Aldmeri Dominion has its eyes on Glenumbra. I wonder what they could want with us? nnTake this letter and these plans to Danain. She's outside of Camlorn.

I presume he wasn't dead when you arrived? Good show.nnYes, this is serious. The Aldmeri Dominion has its eyes on Glenumbra. I wonder what they could want with us?nnIs this why Daggerfall's forces aren't here? I wonder....
Vartisans are skilled practitioners of the art of maintaining the Varlines passing through Tamvir, Varlines which keep the Altmer magic flowing strong.

Very astute. As a rule, Intricants maintain Imago Serries spread across Varyllis, but the Imagerie is Langdruun's crown jewel. He would not trust it to any but me, and I am still close enough to the Kinhouse to respond quickly if the need arises.

As you must know, the Altmer are a race of studious and isolated people - Vartisans doubly so.The disruption the Maormer have wrought on the Varlines has pushed some of the less stable Altmer over the edge. Hainen is among these unfortunates.
In my experience, there are but two methods for luring a wild beast. Which way would you like to know about?
I apologize for delaying you. When you confront the Serpent, I will be at your side.
I will gladly assist you in defeating the Serpent. Once you have the support of the other two Guardian Exemplars, the Warrior will summon us all to join you in the assault.
