Thank you, <<1>>. We'll get back to work straight away.

I speak? Words are poison. Do not listen to them. They make your mind slip away. Slimy fish words. The bad dreams come into you from clean white pages.nnWait, where am I? I was in the library, reading, and my book... attacked me!

It is not her voice she wants back...nnIsrisa was a talented vocalist, yet knew her voice was frail compared to the Fane of Breath. She summoned me and made a pact. I would lend divine power and grace to her simple mortal voice... for a time.

It's not her voice she wants back...nnIsrisa was a talented vocalist, yet knew her voice was frail compared to the Fane of Breath. She summoned me and made a pact. I would lend divine power and grace to her simple mortal voice... for a time.

I may have forgotten to mention how long she could borrow the voice and that once I withdrew it she would be mute. But alas, she cared only of the gift, not the price.nnYet, I am not unreasonable. Should you entertain me, I will give the gift again.
We could play a riddle game, you could silence Mara's Singing Cats, or you could demonstrate your Numinous ability to cheat death.
I present you with a Riddle and you solve it. You will want to answer correctly.nnShall I pose a riddle?
Some of the cats that roam the Fane of Breath can sing. I grow tired of their yowling. Bring me their tongues.
Die. nnThen return to me. I will watch you end your life. It would be delightful to watch a mortal escape fate. To make things interesting, I will place you in a perilous location.
We could play a riddle game, you could silence Mara's Singing Cats, or you could demonstrate your Numinous ability to cheat death.
I present you with a riddle and you solve it. You will want to answer correctly.nnShall I pose a riddle?
Some of the cats that roam the Fane of Breath can sing. I grow tired of their yowling. Bring me their tongues.
Die. nnI will place you in a perilous location and watch you end your life. If you are a Numinous and the stories are true, return to me after you have cheated death.
I will play unusually fair and pose a riddles in your own language.
I pull down the sky,nsmash mountains flat,nand swallow every sea.nnYou may run and runn'neath moon and sunnand never come close to me.
In the night we arrive unbiddennIn the day we appear to be hidden.nnWhat are we?
Nightmares may be forgotten, but they never hide.
I did not doubt for a moment that I could rely on you. You have my thanks, <<1>>.
Where are the oceans dry, the mountains flat, and the sky can never be seen?
Should you find yourself searching for the sky in the middle of the desert, tilt your head back and look up.nnYou are incorrect.
The sky is not obscured in every dream.nnYou are incorrect.
It pleases me you answered incorrectly.
A simple answer to a simple question.nnYou are correct.
It pleases me you answered incorrectly.
My mother has always been sensitive to fluctuations in the Varlines. When they were disrupted, it affected her badly.nnIt did not help that she was at the Tower of Many Bindings at the time.
Bring me the tongues of the Singing Cats, not just any stray.

An archival tower in the southeast of Varyllis. Many of our oldest tomes are stored within.nnThe written word has power in Summerset. When the Varlines were disrupted, many books took on a semblance of life, and attacked the librarians.
Which do you think Isrisa values more, her voice or her beauty?nnIf I return her voice to her, she will turn into a cat. Otherwise, I will return her voice to one of the wandering strays.
Have you ever noticed how many Singing Cats there are in the Fane of Breath?
Have you ever noticed how many Singing Cats there are in the Fane of Breath?
Something terrible happened in Moira's Hope. Merchants travelling through the small village tell tales of carnage and slaughter.

Aha! There we go again. Direct and forward.nnI accept partial blame for what's happened to this city. A miscalculated judgment of trust on my part has resulted into power falling into the wrong hands. nnYou've dealt with the minions already, but….

As much as it pains me to admit, I am partially at fault for the current state of Rivenspire. I'm merely attempting to correct a mistake I made placing my trust in strangers.nnI need your help. Doing this alone is not an option for us.

You know how to fight, I'll give you that. nnSlaying Montclair was the easy part. He was a mindless minion bent on destruction. The foe you'll face next is much stronger. nnIt's settled! A test! We wouldn't want you getting yourself killed. would we?
I am not prone to rumormongering. However, those who are say that Animated Books have been seen flying away from the Tower of Many Bindings, which lies on the southwestern side of the Stonewake.

Ring the Blessed Bell to unleash a wave of magical sound in whatever direction you face. To most creatures the sound is mild and pleasant, but the uncouth Maormer will be overwhelmed by its onslaught.

Ah, <<1>>. We watched you raise the Var Lens with Ameralee.nnAs soon as the lens was in place, my mother stilled. She is more coherent now. It will take time and rest for her to recover completely, but you have my gratitude.

Yes! Oh, Mara's blessing on the little things but they're constantly underfoot. nnWould you like one? It's the least I can do after all you've done for me! nnGraymalkin is an excellent mouser. I'm sure her kittens will grow up to be the same.
All right, just let me know if you change your mind!
Oh, wonderful.  nnHere, <<1>>, take this one in the basket.
Delia spends most of her time in the barrows. She's the gravedigger. nnShe even knows which heirlooms belonged to which families. She'd probably even bury things for you, if you asked!

You would too, Optimate, if you could even begin to comprehend the limitless depth of my knowledge.nnSo. Beyond displaying your unwarranted impertinance, was there something else you wished to accomplish here?
I am King Ranser's general, the commander of the elite forces of Shornhelm.nnAt least, I was. Now I command naught but dust, while Ranser himself leads his undead legion.

Has it been so long that Ranser's War was forgotten? Know that King Ranser was proud and his army strong. He attacked Wayrest.nnBut this action united all of High Rock against him. After a year of conflict, he met the Orcs here in final battle.

Surely, you jest. King Ranser was the king of Shornhelm and all of Rivenspire, a man of great and terrible pride.nnHe and the court of Wayrest had many conflicts, but none so great as when Wayrest's prince spurned his daughter's hand.

Yes, for I am the hand that slew him upon the battlefield. If you seek the crown, I must know your motives.nnCease your destruction of the Tor, and I will seek you out. Then perhaps I will aid your quest.
I don't know. Mother always said I was hopeless when it comes to this sort of thing.nnWhat do you think? Is it a mistake to chase Guendeline? Is Khalisah the better woman?

There is one more thing I need to do to atone for my actions. I need to make sure the Crown of Shornhelm is returned to its rightful liege.nnThe crown is in the chest behind me. Take it and bring it to Chancellor Karine in Hoarfrost Downs.

We must restore the purity of water, air, and earth.nnThe spirits of the land yearn to help us, but Angof's corruption chokes every attempt they make to reclaim our glen. Worse still, one of Angof's minions has corrupted our Wyrd Tree.

Search our glen for three signs: water, earth, and air. Touch the signs. Through you, each spirit of the land will manifest.nnIf you can defend each one from Angof's corruption, they can restore purity to our glen, leaving Angof's minion vulnerable.

The corruption sickened the others. It made them flee.nnI am our Wyrd Tree's keeper. We are bonded. Only I was strong enough to stay, though I am as sick as our tree.nnWyress Gwen, on a hilltop to the south, seeks a cure. If you would help, find her.
Speak, then. My time here grows short.

The Altmer Choir vanished just before they were supposed to perform for the Kinlord. There is however, an odd ...warbling... coming from the bridge to the northwest of the Isquer Kinhouse, a location the choir normally chose for their recitals.

The priestesses of Mara at the Fane of Breath are reknowned musicians. Among their singers, young Isrisa's voice is believed the most powerful and haunting. Anyone travelling through Summerset should hear her perform once!

Keep clear of the crumbling cliffs south of the Orchestral Gardens! Last night our students were awakened by the sound of a large piece falling into the sea. One even said she heard cries for help, but I told her she was dreaming.
And to you as well, friend!
This is the Tyrsicor Collegium. Our Kinship is reknowned for its mastery of matters musical. Only the brightest are invited to study the art of sound-magic at Tyrsicor.
I thought as much when they came trotting home.nnHere they are now. Take better care of them this time.
My poor Isrisa - I care for her too much to play such a vile game with her fate. It is best if you decide.

Gracious, no! The cats of Isque may sing, but they do not speak.nnNo, I am a mer of advanced years. I find it far easier do business abroad through the vessel of this marvellous enchanted cat.nnIs she not sweet? Scratch her behind the ears.
Oh, it lies abed in the upper stories of the Kinhouse. It is quite decrepit, I fear. Thus my use of this familiar.nnReally, you should scratch her behind the ears. She quite likes that.

Not all of them. Only Mara's blessed cats. They are tended to at the Fane of Breath, the temple complex that lies north of the Isque Kinhouse.nnAsk me not how they sing. The priestesses do not speak of the matter. Perhaps it is a sacred mystery.

We are reknowned across Tamriel for our arts of music. The finest instruments and the most majestic symphonies issue from this very Kinhouse. We have moved stones to tears, and struck birds to silence with shame.

I expect you are a Numinous of surpassing ability then, eh?nnLike most Kinhouses in Summerset, Varyllis has lost its Varla Lens. Damaged or some such. Restoring it might convince Kinlord Langdruun to offer the Queen Felballin's Baton of Fidelity.
It was full of water just a few days ago. Now, nothing but mud and dust!nnIt must be a curse! My father says it's the vampires, that they've brought a curse down on the entire kingdom!

You know. The blood-sucking, evil, somewhat romantic kind. Surely you've heard of them? They've always been around, but lately there are more than ever.nnDon't tell my father, but I actually think they're kind of exciting.

Well, in addition to the vampires, I've heard talk about people turning into mindless bloodfiends. They say Moira's Hope is crawling with the disgusting creatures. And don't ask about what's happening to the west.nnWe're cursed, I tell you. Cursed!

You mean you would actually trade me that for this unworthy beast? If you are willing to do that, you are as dumb as the damn horse!nnWhat will you do with him? He's only good for hauling heavy loads, and he's not even much good for that!

Ha! You are crazy as that dog-loving boy Handre! This horse does not want to be free. He would not even know what to do. nnI will trade with you, but no taking it back. You will feel like a fool when the stupid thing just stands there.
Do you think I'd rather beg than work? But work for a dust-sweep isn't as common as it used to be. And a man's got to do what he can. I have a family to feed, after all.
Bless you and bless this glinting gift. Tonight I will turn this clanking metal into bread and turnips for my family's supper. A feat greater than the most talented alchemist can conjure, eh?
Who can say? What with this civil war and all, maybe people don't care as much about cleanliness as they used to.nnI'm just trying to make ends meet, and economics was never my strong point.

They come in the night! Clawing! Biting! They have the faces of friends and lovers, but they're monsters! Monsters!nnI tried to run, but I was trapped! In my own house! That's when my own husband turned on me! I had to kill him. I had no choice.

Monsters! Who cares what the technical term for them is? The kind of monsters that used to be our friends and loved ones. Until the blood cravings take them. And the madness. And the rage.nnSoon all of Rivenspire will be filled with these creatures!

No! He wasn't my husband. Not any more. He was a monster! He came back from Northpoint, and the next morning he … changed. There was rage in his eyes. Madness.nnHe was an animal and I had to put him down. May the Divines forgive me!

I, uh, work in the Mages Guild. At least, I used to work there.nnWhen Jerwinna … that is, Master Leonace … left for <<1>>, she released all apprentices from service until further notice. That's given me more time to catch up on my studying!

Once, I was the master of a vast enterprise, brokering deals, trading goods. Now I'm nothing but another destitute drunk—thanks to those vampires. nnAnd do you know who suffers? My daughter, that's who.
Belle? She's outside, fetching water. She's such a smart young woman, and I've brought her down with me and all my talk of vampires. What kind of father am I?nnPardon me, but I need another drink.

They have everything to do with it! Oh, they may have looked like Montclair ruffians when they trashed my cart and took everything I had. But make no mistake! There were vampires among their ranks!nnNow my daughter and I have nothing. Nothing!
If you're looking for my lazy husband, he's out somewhere, doing who knows what.nnI work two jobs to keep us fed, but they call him the dust-sweep. It breaks my heart.

Well, things might be worse elsewhere. We at least have a house here, such as it is. I don't want to end up living in some raggedy tent, worrying about wild animals—or worse—attacking. nnShornhelm is my home. That's where I'll stay.
He was, but there isn't much call for his services of late. Me? I take care of the miller's children every morning and then clean noble manors all afternoon.nnI'm wiped out!

I know your kind. You befriend me and then you take everything I've collected for your own! Well, I see right through your plan and I'm having no part of it! nnNow get away before I scratch your eyes out! I have sharp nails, you know!
I will be. The pain will pass. My son carried me home after the … incident. He's been taking care of me since.

I was outside, watching Countess Tamrith walk by, and I commented about how beautiful she was. Next thing I know, one of Montclair's ruffians struck me and knocked me down.nnIf not for my son, I'd probably still be lying out there.
He's a good son, but I fear he might try to avenge me for the insult of the … incident.

No, no. She isn't blood-cursed, or anything like that. She just mentioned how lovely the Countess was, and one of those Montclair thugs punched her.nnMy mother has protected me my whole life. Now it's my turn to watch over her.
I did once! Not anymore, it seems. I hardly have a copper to my name. I'm a stablehand with no stables to speak of. How can I expect her to even notice me?nnI'm sorry, what were you saying?

Who else? She's a delicate flower among the debris, my darling Belle. I see her at the bar sometimes with that sad look on her face.nnI wish I could take her away from all this, but look at me! I can barely take care of myself!

Because our constantly bickering nobles are the reason Montclair decided to strike out on his own.nnI admire the High King immensely, but why he thought setting up a triumvirate instead of just selecting a local ruler, I'll never know.

Yes. Some refugees from Calmorn must be werewolf spies in human form.nnUse this Potion of True Nature on Camlorn Refugees and Guards. It destroys any illusion.nnOh, and keep this quiet. If people know werewolves are about, no one will trust anyone.
What would you like to know?

He's a Reachmage unlike any we've ever seen.nnHe wields both necromancy and nature magic. The combination is corrupting Glenumbra.nnAt the moment, he's the most dangerous threat facing the Daggerfall Covenant.

We serve the High King of the Daggerfall Covenant and all the territories that compose it.nnWhen their armies can't deal with a threat, the High King sends us.nnDuke Sebastien, the ruler of Camlorn, requested our help after Camlorn was lost.

No doubt you've seen the refugees in Aldcroft.nnAn invading army has sacked Camlorn. Many of the survivors claim the army was composed entirely of werewolves.nnTheir leader, General Faolchu, is has been infecting peasants with lycanthropy.
What would you like to know?

In life I was Coty Danain, Captain of the Guard protecting my mistress, Raven Direnni. nnHer magic kept us from harm. Our steel protected her.nnThe time of the Direnni Hegemony is long past, but our oath to our mistress remains.

Many years ago, the Alessian Order invaded Glenumbra and warred with the Direnni Hegemony. nnThe Direnni were mostly Altmer, the ancestors of your Bretons.nnAiden and Raven Direnni led their forces to repel the Alessians. They won, but at great cost.

The Direnni Hegemony ruled Glenumbra in the First Age. Two Altmer brothers ruled: Ryan and Aiden Direnni.nnTheir cousin, Raven, was one of the most talented sorceresses ever known.nnMany Bretons are descended from those early Direnni.

After forsaking her elven masters, Alessia, the Slave Queen, started her own religion.nnHer empire, the Alessian Order, ruled all of Cyrodiil in the First Age.nnAfter her death, her fanatical followers made her a saint and tried to conquer the world.

I've seen some unsavory types rooting around behind buildings. They might have stashed their ill-gotten gains out of sight.nnI suspect some of the thugs around town might still be carrying their stolen valuables. There's only one way to find out.
As you would, Optimate. Prepare yourself.
I'm very glad you said that.  Take this key.  nnThe key is to the Northpoint Garrison.  Give it to my Nord contact in the lighthouse, and bring what they give you to me.
You couldn't pay me to do what Alchemist Thetis is doing. nnHe's out there all alone, surrounded by who-knows-what up at the tarn.
Alchemist Thetis is very brave. nnHe didn't even take a guard with him when he left to do his research up at the tarn!
They say Alchemist Thetis plays a flute to charm the beasts near the tarn. nnThat's how he can live among them and see what's happening in the water.
The soldiers at Farwatch Tower are normally good at giving us fair warning of attack.nnHowever, we've heard nothing since Camlorn fell. nnI hope the tower is all right.
There's a garrison out at Farwatch Tower keeping watch over the northern coast.nnThey didn't get caught up in Camlorn's misery, thank the Eight!
Aldcroft wouldn't be full of refugees if the guards on Farwatch Tower had done their job. They should have noticed the attack on Camlorn.nnPutting more troops on the north coast is a waste of time!

I've lived in Fell's Run all my life, and I'm as stubborn as any Breton here. nnStill, I'll never understand why so many folks throw up their hands at the Orcs coming here.nnMoney is money! Their coins are as good as any others!

There's always been a few here and there, mostly working as mercenaries. After the sack of Shornhelm, some of the Orcs came north to settle.nnThe first few years were hard, but I think people are getting used to seeing them around now.
Oh, Grok's harmless. He just can't hold his liquor. nnI let him stay here because he entertains the customers with his war stories. Plus, he tips well.nnAlways remember: tip well.
It's probably nothing. This wouldn't be the first time she's run off. She always comes back a few days later, cold and hungry.nnI'm sure she'll come back soon.
Me? I'm just a farmhand. I used to work on Normar's fields, but he… well, he sold them off when he became mayor.nnNow I do odd jobs for people around town.
Let me guess. You've never seen someone milk a cow? nnJessa here is one of the best producers in town.nnCan't stand milk myself. So chalky and rank. Ugh.
About a fortnight ago, I got conscripted as a watchman after Old Themond got too drunk to stay awake. nnUsually, I stick to honest labor. If it's good work at a good wage, I'll do it.

I've been working as the treasurer here for, what, two months now? nnPutting down my sword was hard, but I do like having a comfortable bed again. It's better than the hard ground we slept on after marching all day.
Soldier? No. I fought for myself. Sometimes it was for money. Sometimes, I just fought to survive.nnOnce you fight for someone else, you become nothing more than a slave. I am no slave.
We'll have more to report once we finish questioning the prisoner. I turned him over to <<1>>.nnBarnabe has him in one of the tents on the hilltop.
Wolves have taken over Camlorn.nnMy cousin's entire family was slain!
Heard any rumors? I've been living in a nightmare! nnTerrible wolves are besieging Camlorn. Some are as big as a bear!
Wolves have completely overrun Camlorn.nnThey're spreading a strange disease.nnUnless they're stopped, they could kill everyone in Aldcroft!

Have you now? Then why do I find these... fetishes around the town?nnFirst we hear tales of undead south of us. Now there's necromancers in our town?nnTake these vile symbols to Thorkan. See if he dismisses my fears now!

You stand in the presence of Leonce Gavendien, rightful heir to the throne of Shornhelm … perhaps not in name or blood, but in deed and intent!nnI have a vision, dear friend. Mayhaps you are intrigued enough to listen, learn, and understand it.

'Tis simply the start of my illustrious empire! I am a Breton, descended from the noble Aldmeri themselves!nnThat fact alone grants me the mandate to rule, and I shall seize my rightful place in history … by force of arms, if necessary!
Would you not be hostile, if your right to rule was constantly dismissed as treasonous?nnIf I cannot win lands by diplomacy, then I will seize them by might!

Even now my men muster an army of allies: Bretons who understand my vision and righteous might. All who stand with me will be rewarded. All who oppose me will fall!nnSeems to me to be a simple choice. Would you not agree, friend?
They might mention something important in front of you if you eavesdrop on their conversations. Likewise, they might have some important parchment or something in their belongings.

You're looking at it. I leave soon to wield it against Faolchu. That Altmer bastard will fall at last.nnI don't know what you're doing here, but I don't question my mistress. I ask only that you speak to her.nnMaybe we'll meet again some day.
If you didn't already pick one up when you were looking for the cure, you will probably have to kill one of the Rooks.
Thank you for collecting the QAT Catnip.  Now I can make stew for Tiny.

Astraela is a steel fist in a velvet glove in a block of ice, but her affection for her people is sincere.nnThere are Maormer invading from the south and the east. At the very least, I expect you shall have to throw them back into the sea.

Isque is holding its own against the Maormer, but its Varla Lens is missing. Kinlord Maldarawo will want it restored.nnMaldarawo is Ayarynne's sharpest critic, if not the most influencial. The only things stiffer than his neck are his compositions!

Fascinating story, actually. A giant avatar of the Serpent constellation slithered up the spire of Genivra's Kinhouse and devoured her Varla Lens.nnRecover her Lens and you will win her Baton of Fidelity.nnThere is no subtext in this, I am sure.

My name's Blaise - Blaise Ascent. I work for Frelie, guarding the town from scavenging beasts and thieves.nnMy family's lived here for generations. I'm not about to let Hoarfrost fall to bandits and brigands.
Me? Not much. I mind the stables. Make sure the horses are fed and watered. Keep them safe from the bandits. That sort of thing.

I'm a cattle wrangler. I ride around these parts, watching people's herds. I've been working for the Edralds for most of the last few years. nnI just came up here to track down a few bulls that had managed to wander off.

Not much to tell. Rumors, mostly. I heard that everyone in Moira's Hope was turned into bloodfiends. And House Montclair attacked the Rivenspire troops over at Hinault Farm.nnPlus, there's the bandits. So I'm leaving, and I suggest you do the same.
Of course I'm upset! Rivenspire's going to Oblivion in an ox cart, and there's not a damn thing I can do about it!
It's certainly better than the question! But why should I expect you to understand? You're not even from around here.nnGo bother someone else. I've got more drinking to do.

Ah, now that'd be Red Bess' ship.nnShe sank off the coast so many years ago, after she attacked Northpoint and tried to run off with half her treasure.nnShe would have succeeded if the mages hadn't blasted her mast to smithereens and foundered her.

They were wounded attacking the Maormer. Or defending against them. All the same, really.nnThe bridge to Sunhold is fortified, and the beaches patrolled. They say there are undead benath the waves as well.nnFoolish, really. We should stave them out.

Burn their supplies. Sink their ships. Sunhold does not have enough to feed them forever. Bottle them up on the island until they start eating their shoes, then attack.nnWe have ships. We should use them here, not send them off to Tamriel!
No, the soldiers line up to bask in my sparkling personality.nnBah.nnTariella promises more help is coming, yet she sends me more corpses than healers.

I heard those damned Bitterkites are taking over the Obsidian Scar. nnThey've made the most of the turmoil there. They're vicious fighters!nnTheir leader is Kitemaster Gra'zagor. They say ten men can't stop him... but one hero should.
This is not good news. Camlorn has already been attacked, and they have plans for Daggerfall as well? You'll need to report this to <<1>> in Deleyn's Mill.
By the Divines! First an attack on Camlorn, and now an invasion here? <<1>>, you have my thanks.
Thank you.  The years may not have been kind to me, but I can still fight.  And better me than my son.nnBetter me than him, after everything that happened.  Tell Balmont to send him home.
<The giant looks to the cave entrance. It seems to understand.>

This is very interesting.nnWe have a traitor in our midst. It's a good thing you discovered this. The Nords are planning to march on our city and take us by surprise.nnTake this to the duchess. It looks like her negotiations with the Nords are over.

I hasjhsjah ahjfahjfh ahfkjashfjkh ajlfhasjkfha hfajkhnnhajkfhasjf ahfjkahfa sfhasfjkahfjkha fhajkfhjaskfh ashfjkashjkfha jkashfjkashf nnhfajfh ahfjkhasfjkahsfjh ahafjkhsjakfh ahfjkahsfjkahf ahjkfhajkshfa hkfjshafjkahjkfhasf jkasfhjaskfhjkashf asjkfh

Kill them all.nnShow them no mercy, for they deserve none! Slay either of the noble House leaders. It is the only way for us to return to the Doomcrag … and the true threat.nnPlease, <<1>>. I need you to do this.

Each Exemplar you speak to can tell you where to go next. You need only ask.nnAfter The Lady, you will choose one of several Exemplars to visit. Pick whichever most appeals to you; all can aid our cause.
You need to ask a total of four to bind their essence into the Welkyn Stone.
The Ritual or The Lord could assist. Go to whichever you most desire. The Lord is a stong yet stern master. The Ritual is wise, but distant.
The Tower, The Shadow, or The Steed could aid your cause.nnThe Tower can see that which is hidden, while the Shadow is itself hidden. The Steed is swift and sure.
The Lady. The Apprentice.nnLady endures. Boring. Nice person. But dull.nnApprentice has great magic. Good! Falls quick to magic. Bad!
Your last stop could be either The Lady or The Apprentice.nnThe Lady is charming and stoic, while The Apprentice has great affinity for magicka.

All of Summerset draws magicka from the Orrery.nnThe Orrery harnesses the celestial magic from the sky by mimicking the positions and motions of the planets with model planets.nnThe Skyharkers are the guardians of the Orrery.

Skyharkers maintain the Orrery. To keep the Orrery's model planets in sync with the actual celestial spheres each of us forms a mental bond with one of the models.nnThe Prime Skyharker forms a bond with all of the model planets at once.
Indeed! Countless young fighters have attempted to capture a Kirin for the Phidian Menagerie but all have failed. We menagerie keepers must continue to dream for such a beast....
Indeed they did, but the Guardians pushed them back. The Maormer have since spread their camps across the southern edge of the Orrery. I fear they may be regrouping.

In addition to model planets, the Orrery is also home to living embodiments of the constellations called Exemplars. The Thief, The Mage, and The Warrior Exemplars protect the other constellations - they are the Guardians.

After completing our apprenticeship each Skyharker is assigned a model planet with which we commune, forming a mental bond. The Prime Skyharker is bound to the Orrery as a whole - mentally connected to every model planet.

For now, I must keep my own counsel on that.nnI can only assure you - and all my subjects - that it was not a decision I reached lightly. If we remain in splendid isolation, all the world may fall to ruin.

Ahh... you do? I see. Of course.nnDo not delay then! The pieces of the Crown must be taken to the Anquillius Forge, where Master Metalwright Sinderon presides. He is familiar with the ritual; speak with him to begin the process.
It is a symbol. A token that a Kinlord offers during votes in council. Giving it to Ayarynne would indicate that Langdruun will support her policy on the Heartlands.

Talk to Langdruun. The best way to find out what someone wants is to ask, eh?nnI doubt he would trust you with the matter of the Varla Lens staright away. I do expect he has some other task that will prove your ability. Not a subtle man, I think.

A crystal, made of meteoric glass. Varla Lenses direct and focus the energy of the Varlines.nnThe Varlines are streams of magicka drawn from the stars.They flow across the land, powering various works of magic.

Suuniqwe was the Prime Skyharker of the Orrery - she oversaw the Skyharkers and kept the model planets aligned with their celestial counterparts. nnDuring the Maormer attack, after Auri-El was thrown down from the sky, she disappeared.

Talk to Langdruun. The best way to find out what someone wants is to ask, eh?nnI doubt he would trust you with the matter of the Varla Lens staright away. I do expect he has some other task that will prove your ability. Not a subtle man, I think.
It is a symbol. A token that a Kinlord offers during votes in council. Giving it to Ayarynne would indicate that Langdruun will support her policy on the Heartlands.

Talk to Langdruun. The best way to find out what someone wants is to ask, eh?nnI doubt he would trust you with the matter of the Varla Lens staright away. I do expect he has some other task that will prove your ability. Not a subtle man, I think.

A crystal, made of meteoric glass. Varla Lenses direct and focus the energy of the Varlines.nnThe Varlines are streams of magicka drawn from the stars.They flow across the land, powering various works of magic.
No. She was leading the Skyharkers in defending the Orrery when suddenly she began screaming... and was gone. The sky went black, then was full of fire, and Auri-El came crashing down.
Maslir, a rival of mine, became a Starblind. He was clearly weak willed. The Orrery is better without such frail Skyharkers.

I know that bandits take over old encampments, sometimes even abandoned villages, and make themselves at home.nnThose leaders divide up and defend their territories like the dogs that they are. They're all over Bangkorai.

A crystal, made of meteoric glass. Varla Lenses direct and focus the energy of the Varlines.nnThe Varlines are streams of magicka drawn from the stars.They flow across the land, powering various works of magic.
It is a symbol. A token that a Kinlord offers during votes in council. Giving it to Ayarynne would indicate that Maldarawo will support her policy on the Heartlands.

Stiff as a Varyllis garden. Stiff as young man on his first pilgrimage to Priestess Vendialara's Fane.nnA terrible secret, really. The leader of Summerset's finest musicians has no ear for music.nnHe is quite good at cultivating roses, though.

A crystal, made of meteoric glass. Varla Lenses direct and focus the energy of the Varlines.nnThe Varlines are streams of magicka drawn from the stars.They flow across the land, powering various works of magic.
It is a symbol. A token that a Kinlord offers during votes in council. Giving it to Ayarynne would indicate that Genivra will support her policy on the Heartlands.
Then I'll stay here, and I'll hope that Frelie has mercy on me. If she doesn't… well, maybe I deserve what's coming to me. I'll tell the truth and bide my time.
You want to think about it? This is my life you're toying with! nnI should have known better than to trust an outsider. What makes you fit to judge what I've done?
Then I'll do it. nnIf Frelie won't take me, I'm sure Shornhelm could use a soldier like me.

Maybe she was right. Maybe I just need to get out of Rivenspire and go my own way.nnThank you, stranger. I don't know what I'll do or where I'll go, but I know what I want now. I want the freedom of the open road.

The Starblind... used to be Skyharkers. They once maintained the Orrery, but now they ravage it.nnVilmo, our new Prime Skyharker, believes Suuniqwe is communicating with them somehow - directing them.

You killed her! My love! My betrothed! nnWe grew up together, fought together. Something turned her, but I know she still loved me.  nnShe's never harmed me, never. I... fed her things. Remains. I... we.... nnWe would have been fine by ourselves.
It is a symbol. A token that a Kinlord offers during votes in council. Giving it to Ayarynne would indicate that Astraela will support her policy on the Heartlands.

We weren't always this way, jumping at every noise, afraid of our own shadows.nnGovran's my younger brother. I brought him up after our parents died in the war.nnIf they take him from me, they'll take away my reason to live. I think they'll kill him.

You'll need to take along a charm. It calms the poor fools down when they get violent.nnDon't attack anyone. Just use the charm. And don't try anything suspicious, or I might not let you back out.nnReady to go in?

Those Cerone brothers are a curse on Koeglin Village: always asking for handouts, but never doing an honest day's work.nnWhere's the money, then? I don't see you carrying a sack of coins large enough to pay for my boat.

Can't you tell? Everyone's gone mad. The ones in here and the ones outside... all of us are mad!nnThey'll kill us soon, when there are too many of us. nnThey're afraid of us. And we're afraid of them. None of us deserve to die.
You get to come and go as you please, don't you?nnFine. Get out of here... while you still can.

By Mara, you're right. I should have seen it. I suppose it was easier to blame Irne rather than see the true cause.nnStill, this doesn't mean Irne's not out to get me! I'll watch him close. Even so... let him know I don't blame him for my boat.

That claw does fit the hole, almost exactly. If you hadn't put it right in front of my face, I wouldn't believe it.nnStill, that doesn't mean Valentin isn't plotting something else! I'll keep an eye out. Can you let him know I'm sorry?
Maybe you're right. Her hunger was growing. It was endless, boundless. Who knows where that might have led?nnI'll go back. Just let me have a few last moments with her.
Irne Guylitte's been raising all sorts of fuss about someone sabotaging boats, down on our docks. Wouldn't surprise me, with all the undesirables around.

Think not of it as killing, but setting them free. nnIt is the only way, <<1>>. If we stand idly by, we will be doomed to an eternity stuck in this twisted realm of shadow visions.nnWe must slay one of the noble houses to return to the task at hand.

I know this weighs heavy on your heart, but it is our only option. We either slay one of the noble house leaders or stay stuck in this life until we wither and die of old age.nnAs much as I enjoy your company, <<1>>, we must do this to continue on.
Of course I am. Are you not?nnIt is however simply another challenge we are thrown up against and must overcome. It's that simple.

When isn't it? Even when the farmers task the lone adventurer with saving their crops, it always involves the slaying of some poor creature that simply lived its life.nnEither bend the creature to your will to live by your standards, or be rid of it.
I... must have power... must have.. flesh!

I've heard of ruins beyond the barrow mounds to the southeast.nnOnce it was a great city, but like everywhere else these days, it's full of Daedra and who-knows-what else.nnThey say there's treasure, though, if that's what you're looking for.

The Battlereeves at the south and east beaches could answer that question better than I. Kill Maormer until they stop coming, I suppose.nnYou do have the advantage of being a Numinous. If killed, you can simply try again.

Astraela heads one of the most powerful Kinships in Summerset, <<1>>. Returning her lands to the status quo will not appease her pride.nnNo, you will need to perform some legendary deed or other. I could not guess what. Do let me know!

Have you not figured it out? nnYou are trapped within her grasp, just as I was. I faltered in my journey. Words of warning fell upon my deaf ears. So many lives were lost because of my ignorance! You cannot let this be your fate. You must go!

This plane you stand in is simply a spell of deception being weaved before you. We can shatter this illusion sending you both back to Doomcrag. This will throw her off guard when this happens. You must strike quickly or your soul will be hers.
What would you like to know?

It should be obvious. The damn lighthouse has gone dark! nnThe fog was thick when we arrived. I expected the lighthouse to warn us when we were near the reefs.nnIf you ask me, someone in Koeglin Village extinguished the lighthouse's flame on purpose!

The Crested Falcon! She's a big girl, she is. She's run aground on an atoll out in the cove. nnThe tough old girl broke her side when we hit, and most of our cargo went spilling into Alcaire Cove.nnI should be out there right now, patching her up.

Mara's Flowing Skirts! I didn't think you'd actually do it! Well done, <<1>>!nnI can get your reward right after you show Constable Sal your proof. He'll get me out of these damnable stocks. nnGo see him straightaway!

According to his orders, Pirate Captain Ra'Dara was behind the destruction of the lighthouse and our missing villagers.nnPerhaps I was wrong about Captain Leon.nnTake this key. Free Captain Leon. Then get him out of my town.

Have you not noticed Veraya's lust for the kill? With every battle fought within this realm the balance tips in her favor. I am already gone; a mindless fool lost on what I thought was love. Do not make that mistake. You must defeat the Dark Council.
Where would we be without our fishing boats? Irne Guylitte down at the docks says someone's been destroying them. Maybe he's doing the destruction himself...
Irne Guylitte says someone's been destroying Koeglin's fishing boats. I say, if Irne's at the docks all day, he knows more about what's going on than he says.

What can I say about the fairest maid in all of Koeglin Village? Hair like buttermilk, blue eyes as deep as the sea itself, skin like porcelain and just as perfect!nnMark my words, friend, I will woe her, even if it takes every bit of gold I earn!

Well, there was this crazy Khajiit just come through here, rambling and raving about his plans to sneak into the Imperial Palisade.nnWild-eyed fellow... called himself Tor I believe. Looked like a skooma eater if ever I saw one. Smelled like one too!

I've tried to kill <<1>>; he's one of the worst on that list. Barely escaped with my life!nnHe used to come down to Evermore, but hasn't been near the city since the illness began. His camp's near Pelin Temple if you want to find him.

You refer to the rumors about my ward, Tor? It is no secret that one has an appetite for trouble, but Ra'Vardo fears his wild nature has led Tor into true danger.nnA brave <<1>> might search for the wayward Tor inside the Imperial Palisade.

Since the lighthouse went out, many ships have run aground and lost cargo in Alcaire Cove. One Captain's loss is another Captain's gain!nnI'm paying well for any valuable salvage you find. Just bring it to me and I'll give you a fair price.

Eh? Eelmer trap eels. Southpoint's renowned for its Ooze-Eel jerky! Or it was, anyway.nnWith Imperials, Altmer and Y'ffre knows who else invading, no one's been able to harvest the traps for months. They're sitting off the shore southeast of town.
I forsake my ancestors, my land, and my queen. I surrender myself to these lowly mer-kind, and grovel.nnI am a prisoner. Can you not see?
Trouble me not with your whys and your whos!nnWho died on the shores of Valenwood? Why should anyone care? I simply wait now, to join them in Aetherius and find peace once more.

There are strange crunchings in the woods outside town. Like trees falling, or being pushed over. Sometimes chanting, small voices, like Bosmer?nnNori-ja will not go outside of town. The Imperials have angered the green life.
Perhaps you could, stranger. But I will not go. The ancestors await my arrival, and I would be ashamed to disappoint them.nnAway with you now, else I shall call the guards.
Our lighthouse went dark not long after the pirates showed up. Some soldiers went to investigate, but we've heard nothing since.nnWhat could it mean?
We've always had pirates along the coast, but no one knows what happened to our lighthouse after this last crew arrived.nnEven the soldiers who went out there have never come back!
They say pirates killed the lighthouse keeper to keep the light from ever being relit. Who knows what horrors go on in the dark now?
Oh, is that what you think? Well, normally I'd tell you to shove off, but I've plucked my share today already. Ha ha!
And you need to mind your own business. Get out of here before I lose my patience with you.
Ha! Let's see if you can make me stop, <<1>>.
What? But why? And who are you?nnAre you threatening me?

Very well. This one has no desire for a fight. She merely sought a bit of extra coin that she might feed the young ones, who wait worried at home with empty bellies.nnNow this one must return to them with neither food nor gold.

You are not one of those mewling Redoran fools, it seems. nnI tire of their incessant questioning. They do not know what this disease can do!nnI have seen it firsthand. Without my guidance, this whole city will perish.

Have the noble houses poisoned your mind?nnWe sought to aid the sick here. We were forgotten by House Redoran and persecuted by House Dres.nnYou have not raised your hand against me, however, so you must be willing to listen.
Is that so? This one does not agree with you, and will continue to search the sands as he sees fit.
Consequences? Do tell, what terror might befall this one should he persist in his honest labors?
Hmm. Persuasive. Please pardon this one's transgressions, and he will depart post-haste!
Ha! This one does not balk so easily, especially from clawless <<1>>s like you.nnProve yourself!

The good stuff! There's plenty to be had with the lighthouse out, and ships running aground.nnCaptain Lash is out right now with some crewers on an island to the south. If you find any decent salvage, you should see her! She'll give you a good deal.

It's been days. Mother enjoyed nightly walks around our farm, and she always returned... until now.nnFather went to look for her, but came back bloodied. He said he was attacked, but he managed to fight them off. At least, that's what he said.

Marea has sent you, has she? nnI've denied her entrance until I'm certain of her motives. She is not of House Redoran. Why does she seek their Hortator?nnI'll consider her request if you will render me some assistance first.

Graverobbers plague the halls of Othrenis.nnFind those who blatantly rob the dead, and those who hide among the our mourners. Slay them. Slay them all.nnI now grant you the blessing of Othrenis. The guardians won't attack unless you provoke them.

Othrenis is a city of the dead, a sacred necropolis where our ancestors rest away from the pain and suffering of our world.nnI attend the spirits to ensure the living do not disturb their eternal slumber.nnTell me, why do you seek the Hortator?

Good. Let it stay that way.nnI have come to where I belong, <<1>>. William nor anyone else will stop me. My dreams have spoken to me and I have been called to my new sisters. This is where I shall stay. Tell my former husband what you wish.

The Ashlanders are blessed by Meridia.nnLong ago our ancestors shielded her from her father when he cast her from the heavens to the mortal plane.nnShe blessed our bloodline, and so we remain untouched by blight.  It is her will.

The Imperial Army. Before they were pushed out, they burned our homes.nnI've heard rumors that the Aldmeri Dominion was at war with the Empire, but never imagined that Southpoint would become a battlefield. We've lost so much.

The Ashlanders are blessed by Meridia.nnLong ago our ancestors shielded her from her father when he cast her from the heavens to the mortal plane.nnShe blessed our bloodline, and so we remain untouched by blight.  It is her will.
Y'ffre's curse on that General Cruor and the Imperial army he leads.nnWhy would the Empire invade Southpoint? Why us? This place is nowhere!

He's in the keep somewhere, but I suspect he's not taking part in the battle preparations. nnWhen he returned just now, he did reiterate the order to attack the Redguards, but he was not well. He seemed sick somehow.
He's hiding somewhere in the keep. I know not where.nnWe'll have to retake the keep from Sir Croix before you'll be able to look for Sir Hughes.
I don't know. Help us retake the keep, and then we can sweep the grounds.nnThough he remains the head of our order, I imagine he must eventually answer for his crimes.
My oath is to Duke Nathaniel.nnSir Hughes hasn't convinced me that Duchess Lakana has turned the duke against his knights. I hold by my oath.
You're right. This doesn't make any sense at all.  My duty is to do what's right, not to blindly follow orders.nnI'm with you.

Well, this place was sure hopping when the Imperials started their attack. Think it's the busiest I've ever seen it. A shame they didn't actually pay for anything.nnNow it's back to the norm. Not as exciting as it was, but I'm fine with that.
You would have me disobey direct orders and turn against Sir Croix? You sound like that coward Sir Edmund.nnYou are an enemy to the order, and I will see you slain.

I've done what I could, but I failed to find Sir Croix. Now I fear he would best me quite easily.nnI need you to do this. I believe the other knights will stand down if we can defeat Sir Croix. Will you face him for me?
Enough blood has been shed this day.nnBlow the siege horn atop the garrison and I will call for an end to the fighting.
They're felling the trees to the north of town and building a palisade to the northwest. Looks like they're wanting to be permanent neighbors.

Why, this is an excellent discovery! Procured from an Imperial Messenger, you say? Most enlightening. I will inform the Thalmor, our alliance's ruling council.nnI must ask you to destroy the message now, to keep it from ever reaching the Imperials.

Prices are higher than normal on food. Most farmers moved closer to Alcaire Keep for safety.nnThere might be one or two farmers out there, but I can only guess at the horrors they have to face every day.
Oh, I dunno, umm... you know... stuff.  Did you want something?

Believe what you will, for it cannot change what is. The Houses bring all around them to ruin with their deals and alliances.nnThe Ashlanders will survive this Blight and rise again, long after the ashes of the Tribunal have settled.

Believe what you will, for it cannot change what is. The Houses bring all around them to ruin with their deals and alliances.nnThe Ashlanders will survive this Blight and rise again, long after the ashes of the Tribunal have settled.
We may not be safe in Alcaire Keep, but we are better off than any farmer that chose to stay out in the fields!nnThere may be one or two farmers still out there.
My family used to live out on one of those farms beyond the Keep.nnI pity those farmers who stayed out there when evil times befell us.

If you head southeast of Alcaire Keep, not that I suggest you do so, you'll go past that Ayleid place.nnWe call it Balarel Ruins now. Don't know what they may have used it for, but it's an evil place.

I don't leave Alcaire Keep after dark. Some say that the Balarel Ruins not far southeast of here are infested with undead creatures!nnThere's enough gone wrong with Alcaire, I don't need the dead to tell me about that!

I've seen lights in the dark wandering Balarel Ruins, not far southeast of here. They say the dead walk at night.nnOr it could just be hoodlums up to no good. Those Ayleid ruins are famous for attracting anything bad.

I have no illusions about my mortality. Though I may die, I will do so knowing I have not betrayed my people.nnI know what House Dres seeks. They wish to blame their troubles on the Ashlanders. I will not give you the satisfaction.
You do not fool me with your honeyed words. All of the Houses conspire to find a reason to persecute the Ashlanders! The Tribunal's hubris is the sole cause of this curse.

Would that we did, we would thank the cause. My people are sheltered from this curse, but those that stray from the true path are doomed to fall.nnTell your Dres taskmaster that, and see the truth in his eyes!
What do you wish to hear, then? That I am responsible for your sins?nnIt matters not, but I will say what you want if it means I will not have to endure any more accusations.
Down the road, just before you reach Firebrand Keep, there's a cave. Windridge Cave.nnFull of brigands. Thieves. Cutthroats.nnMy neighbor's one of them.
We used to store cheese at Windridge Cave, between Balarel Ruins and Firebrand Keep.nnLately, it's full of brigands and the like. They probably ate all our cheese.
When I was a child, I played in a place called Windridge Cave, a bit northwest of Firebrand Keep. I used to feel safe there.nnNow it's full of trash, filth, and brigands.
What would you like to know?

When a Knight of the Flame enters our order, he's given a sword from our forge: a Sword of the Flame.nnThat sword is his very life. No other may use it.nnWhen a knight falls in honorable battle, one of our brothers must return his sword to the flame.

Sir Croix and I followed different paths, but we both wanted to preserve the Knights of the Flame. nnAll who died on both sides died for that. Each one found an honorable death in glorious combat.nnA Knight of the Flame could ask for no better fate.
Your victim seems distracted. Do you try and pickpocket?

That s'wit thinks he controls all the shipping around here, but he doesn't! We could do just fine without his meddling.nnI used to run a legitimate business, and thanks to Orvona, I have to struggle to make my books look innocent!
What, you think he actually deals with his shipping "enterprises?" I'm his cover, and he needs me if he's going to stay in business. Why, I think he should be paying me for my services!
All right! You've made your point. Here's Sugar's protection. And if you repeat anything I've said to you, I'll make sure you pay dearly.

Do you even know what you're doing for him? No, you probably don't even care. I bought this contract from him fairly, and now he wants it back?nnWell I'm not selling — you'll have to take it from my cold, dead hands!
No… wait! Here, take it! Sugar can keep his blood money. I hope the Blight takes you both!
Ha! He'll never be able to tell the difference, I assure you.nnHere, take the contract, and I'll be gone by the time the tide comes in. I never want to see these shores again.

I don't think so. Sugar got his claws on my friend's debt contract, and I've only just gathered enough money to buy it from him.nnI thought Sugar might turn on me. I made a forgery of the real contract… would you take that instead?
Wonderful. Let me take them off your hands. Sugar will speak with you now. Please be polite.
Valenwood was never a friendly place, but there are things in the woods to the east... Large, shambling things that I've only glimpsed before running back to town.

Some of the locals are hearing strange noises in the forest to the east. We haven't seen anything - surely anything hostile would attack.nnIt's probably just Thunderbugs, but given all that's happened, who can blame them for being nervous?
I was here because the refugees were hearing noises in the woods. I thought it was a lot of bunk, myself.nnI was wrong. <<1>> received word that there's a village of Blacksap Bosmer to the east.

Of course I did! I wasn't going to wake up with a dagger in my back or poison in my mead. nnI packed up and got out of there as fast as my cart would go. Almost made it to, but these damned goblins decided they wanted a piece of me as well.
I did not ask you to exchange pleasantries with a criminal! nnHe is causing unrest at a most delicate time.nnIf you lack the stomach for this task, I will have to hire another.

That's a longer story than you think.nnThe important thing is that they don't like Altmer, they don't like Khajiit, they don't like our Camoran King. If you see any, avoid them.nnOr kill them. That would be better for us, really.

What? Why would you say such a thing?nnBravosi assured me we've evacuated everyone who can be saved to the temple.nnOnce he has dealt with the criminals in their district, the afflicted will be allowed to return home.

That demon! How coy of him to send someone in his place.nnI was going to let him hide in the bushes a bit longer. I supposed it's childish, but I can't help teasing him.nnAs for his pants, I'll return them. All I ask is that you dance for us.

Giles, Idah, Luc, and Diane are my dearest friends. All of them crave novelty.nnYou must dance for us. Entertain us! Let the music take you!nnPlease, find my friends around the springs and dance for them. When you're done, dancing fool, return to me.
Oh, aye? One of them Dominion folk, are you?nnCan't say I care much for your type - but I guess you're better than the Imperials. I'll lay off the bodies… for now.
How'd you know? Who sent you?nnWas it Ama? Well, I'm not done poisoning the mead yet.nnTell her I'll be a while.

Well, one of the Oscent boys was making fun of me, so I thought I'd poison the mead and give it to him.. nnHe comes around every night, as predictable as sunset.nnDon't worry. He won't suffer… much. This stuff is strong.

By the Eight, you're right. I'll just have to cosh him in the head after dark.nnOkay, okay. I won't hurt him. The Oscent family's all over Alcaire. They'd come get me anyway. I know it.nnWe've got to destroy the poisoned mead before it's served.

A worshipper of Herma Mora. nnWe are blessed with an incurable penchant for mischief - an affliction we are more than happy to indulge.nnI see the sparkle of a rascal in your eye. The Imperials to the south provide ample opportunities to wreak havoc.

All ruined! Orvona will not be pleased. But, you have done as he asked, so his ire will not be directed at you.nnThe slaves were blighted when they arrived. Orvona tries to avoid dealing with them, but the early stages of Blight are hard to detect.

We sent a caravan to Omaynia a few days ago, and Orvona believes it carried more of these blighted slaves.nnI have no doubt they succumbed to the Blight soon after. They couldn't have made it much farther than Marshmine, if you wish to find them.

The Thrambles is one of the oldest parts of Grahtwood - trackless and primeval. Because of the twisting, confusing trails we never hunted here.nnThe Imperials changed that when they cut the flow of supplies through Haven's port to the south.
How wonderful! Dominique and I do not often see eye to eye, but she does have excellent taste in entertainment.nnDance as you will.
How thoughtful of her! Dominique certainly knows how to entertain us. nnWe knew those dreugh could never appreciate the hot springs as much as we do.nnWell, then, dance away!
Wonderful! Marvelous!nnDominique has such great ideas for entertainment, eh? nnWell, don't keep me waiting. Dance!
This is terrific, my dear!nnDominique told us removing those dreugh eggs would make the hot springs more exciting. She was right!nnDance away!

Dro'tahn - "Grandfather Tahn" - is a great senche tiger. He's prowled the Thrambles for many years. If you see him and don't have friends with you - run.nnOf course, you may not see him. In that case, we'll send your valuables home.

We're hunters. Well, I guess most Bosmer in the Valenwood are hunters in one way or another.nnWe are archers. We specialize in long-distance shooting. It's a difficult art. You need a strong arm, a sharp eye, and a feel for the wind.
I appreciate that, my dear, but what of me?nnAm I to be the only one in this venture who lacks for entertainment?nnCome, dance for me as you danced for my friends. Dance for me!

I imagine dear Mazhe is getting a bit chilly without them. He could have had them sooner ... if he knew how to dance.nnOpen the chest beside the pool. The pants are inside it.nnOh, and do let Mazhe know that I'm thinking of him, my dear.

I know who sent you. But there's no need to kill me! The slaves are free, and I'm certainly in no position to pose a threat to them.nnLook at me! I'll probably die in the next fortnight from Blight. Will you not have mercy on me?

Didn't say. Probably one of these scamps. They're all over the farm, but they weren't here until... well, around the time my mother disappeared.nnShe always took the same route: north along the road to the bridge, down the river, and back.

I wish to tell you that my death was noble and that it meant something. Sadly, I was betrayed by my brother and sister Knights. They were the ones who sealed the cave trapping me with the Four. Still, I should have fullfilled my vow.

The Band of Four in my time, now they are the Fallen Four. When alive, they raided the countryside taking what they wanted and murdering those who stood in their way. How they and I are back as spirits is unknown to me.

Yes. After I pursued the Four into this cave, my fellow knights must have decided that it was better to trap us in this cave versus risk the Four's possible escape or the lives of more knights. A cowardly decision...

I vowed to bring the Four to justice. Regardless of circumstance, it was my duty to fulfill my vow. But it was the four who killed me. They fell upon me, and while I struck one a mortal blow, they triumphed in the end. I am shamed even in death.
No. The cave has been opened recently by graverobbers seeking the wealth of the Four. They meet an untimely end I am afraid, and end up serving the Four...
I'm afraid I'll only be able to answer questions relating to our... task we've asked you to complete. You are a stranger here. I'm sure you understand.

Mandran Veloth and Orvona are shipping partners. But now with the Ordinators keeping their eyes on the shores, he thinks to cut Orvona off.nnHe is an important contact for us, but we cannot let this insult go without recompense.

Delte Sedrane came to strike a deal with Sera Orvona, and in his generosity, he did not realize the value of the contract he sold.nnSera Orvona does not take well to the fact that she swindled him, and simply wants his property back.

Ah, please keep your voice down when asking about that. Sera Orvona had a bad turn of luck at cards a fortnight ago.nnA Dunmer named Alam Sernsi took advantage of this, and won the very cufflinks off of his coat. Get them back any way you can.

We obtained a potion from Durak, a wise orc who leads the Spirit Wardens of Pariah Abbey to the north. The potion prevents us from dreaming.nnDurak believes The Fervor affects those who dream, and I have no reason to doubt him.

I don't understand what's happening. I hope Mother's all right.nnBy Arkay, I hope she's still alive!nnPlease, talk to Father. Maybe the sight of this will snap him out of his drunken reverie. nnHe's somewhere at the farmhouse to the northwest.
Oh? What of it? nnSeeing my name on a list doesn't mean anything. nnYou should keep to your own business, and not barge in on ours!
Why? What have you heard? nnI'm not even allowed to stamp shipments, much less inspect them!nnHouse Dres doesn't even want to know about its own fort. This cannot be a good portent.
Where did you find that? Was it you? Did you kill my Pasqal? Give it to me!
Oh my. Oh yes. I haven't seen that in years. I had thought it lost foresver. May I have it?

No, I'm Colovian. There were a lot of us living in Haven before the Imperials invaded.nnNot everyone in Grahtwood is Bosmer. The Khajiit come from Elsweyr, to the east. Since the Dominion was founded, there are a lot of Altmer here, too.

You'll find lovely windflowers to the northeast, but there are other flowers nearby.nnDisgusting acanthe grow to the southeast. Go northwest, and you'll be among the putrid lunarias. Celsia infest the fields to the northwest.

They're as pale as the moon. Some say the lunaria flower speaks of a night with one's true love beneath the stars.nnI say they're not worth the trouble. After the blossoms are plucked, they die as quickly as a man's interest.

Windflowers are like love's first kiss. nnTheir delicate blossoms of pink look so fragile. A breeze could carry them away!nnTreat them with love and tenderness and they flourish, like a marvelous romance!
Some say celsia's pale yellow beauty matches the dazzling flowers in the gardens of the Divines.nnTo me, they're smelly, messy things that should be fed to pigs.

The acanthe's numerous blossoms are a beautiful shade of pink.nnI've heard it said they stretch to the sun as if reaching for Aetherius.nnI don't think so. To me, they grow like weeds. They should be killed on sight before they ruin a garden.

I hate lunaria above all else.nnSee how the blossoms are already turning brown? They don't last. It's a waste to pick them.  nnHow could Ra'ud ignore my wishes? Tell Ra'ud I'll never speak to him again.

Ah! My favorite!nnDoes Ra'ud think I'm fragile enough to require constant, tender care? I would not squander a chance to receive such lavish attentions!nnI'm pleased by his gift. Tell Ra'ud to come to me as soon as he can.

I hate celsia. They may be beautiful, but when I touch their sap, my skin bursts into an uncomfortable and unattractive rash.nnHow could Ra'ud ignore my wishes? Tell Ra'ud I'll never speak to him again.
How interesting that Ra'ud would present me with a bouquet of acanthe.nnI hate acanthe. Its scent is like rotting flesh.nnHow could Ra'ud ignore my wishes? Tell Ra'ud I'll never speak to him again.

Precious little.nnThe Bosmer are always up for a fight, but the Thornvenom tribe has turned murderous. They've gone mad.nnMy men think it has something to do with Selene and her webs.nnOf course, I'm a fighter, not a sage. I don't really know.

Many methods exist to make them, but Breton fireworks are the best!nnMages lock magical power inside granular sand, then, imbed those vials inside flying sticks of wood. After launching, they explode in midair, creating a marvel of color and sound!
How did you get this? Took it off some corpse I'll wager. Yes, it is mine, and I'd like to have it back.
My mother's hairpin. Yes. Yes. It is mine. I don't know how you found it and I don't care. Please, may I have it?

Help me? You have to stop me!nnStop me from killing Lakana again and again!nn I see Lakana... I see myself... the blade... the blood... I can't look away!nnLakana! What have I done? Will I ever find absolution for this unforgivable crime?
My dreams sometimes frighten me. I heard that they created a potion up at Pariah Abbey the keeps one from dreaming!
What do I look like? A gossip monger?nnAs it happens, I do know that many of those in Pariah Abbey never come to Reywell. They sleep dreamlessly all the time, thanks to some potion they made.
Not long ago,  the leader of Pariah Abbey...I forget his name...created a potion that prevents him from dreaming.
I've seen several matches at Hammerdeath Arena. If you have not seen the gladiators fighting for their lives, you should do so.nnVery entertaining, especially the pathetic pleas for freedom.
Have you been to Hammerdeath Arena to watch the games? It's quite a spectacle with all that fighting in the pits.nnI won quite a lot betting on their last champion.
If you're looking for a good fight, go to Hammerdeath Arena. Many of their best fighters are former slaves up against some professional fighters.nnThe events are exhilarating!
Yes, I'm all right … but not absolved. I ordered the Knights of the Flame to rebellion. I murdered the duchess. I betrayed the duke. nnThese stains on my honor cannot be washed away.
Wait! nnI apo… apol… - I'm sorry for my words! I am in your debt if you would help me stranger, yadda yadda so forth and so on. nnWill you untie me now?

H-how did..? You found my locket?nnMy husband and I went for a walk in the woods. We wanted to have a picnic. See nature. But there were these... these horrible bugs.nnHe attacked them. Told me to run. I didn't look. I didn't look back. The sounds...
Can you? I was so afraid. I have no idea where I am. I think the way out lies to the southeast.nnWould you mind escorting me? I don't think I could make it alone.

I didn't… interfere.  Exactly.  Maybe slightly.nnIt's just that there's something different about you.  I may be just a lowly initiate, but even I can see that.nnI'll tell her the truth, which is that you're immune.  I hope we meet again <<1>>.
Windridge caves? Found it? Unlikely. Let me take a look...
Philippe's old sword. Yes, I recognize it. I made this for a knight in training, a long time ago.

That axe? I see that axe every night. The axe that slaughtered my family. The axe that took my parents and brought me here as a child. Is that why you are here? To strike the final blow and end my servitude?
This axe haunts me. I know it from my childhood. This was the axe that was used to slaughter my family and bring me to this cursed place as a servant. I should like to have it... and destroy it.
Yes! Please help me. I don't want to end like my hus-nnI don't want to die in here. Please.

They are nothing. Feathers and stone. Twine and hope.nnThe nobles often seek Ashlander magics. I give them these. I tell them they will fulfill whatever dream they desire.nnThe afflicted don't know the talismans are worthless.
Ah, yes, I have those here.  Take some.  Good for the Blighted Outlanders or small children to play with... not much use for anything else.

Look to my left and you can see Southpoint - or what's left of it. nnBut maybe you want Elden Root, that the, heh, "High Elves" made into the capital. Go on through town and follow the creek trail northeast.

Remembering the shore of Ookvoot.nnRemembering all the treasure! nnSadness when the treasures became scarce.nnGreat joy when Knock invented our Scavenger Hunt!nnWill <<1>> be participating in the hunt?
This is from the Ashlanders? Is it.. is it the cure for the affliction?
We accept this in payment for Solon the slave. He is free to go, as are you.nnNow get out of here.
Great joy!nnCompeting with Hoom and Wud.nnSwimming to the wrecked ship to the south.nnFetching me something shiny, something pointy, something clangy, and something round!nnGreat joy!
Expressing understanding.nnSympathizing with the stranger.nnPreferring the warmth and safety of Knock's cave.
Admiring the exquisite nature of these items! nnAnticipating their display in Elder Knonk's cave hereafter.nnStating disappointment with Hoom and Wud.nnAwarding the <<1>> the prize!
Revelling in his victory over Wud.nnNever forgetting his new friend's assistance.nnGreat joy.
Gloating at the defeat of the ignoble Hoom!nnWitnessing Hoom's expression of despair!nnPlaying fair. Awarding <<1>> the prize.

The Grand Melee is a spectacle like nothing you've ever seen! nnThe melee is open to all. Anyone can fight! Our combatants must face both the beasts and each other.nnAnyone who slays five enemies and survives receives a winner's purse of gold!

Those who perish do so in the most glorious way ... in battle!nnPerhaps you lack the stomach to face the peril real gladiators confront. Maybe you should go to Reywell and join the soft, pretty things there.nnWhat say you? Are you a lamb or a wolf?
Click Goodbye to Advance Mura's AI State (Only Available if you have a stack count of GM Move)
Yes, of course! I'll go.nnThank you.
This little bundle of rocks and feathers? It doesn't look like much. nnAre you sure this is supposed to cure me?
What is this? A rock?  nnI've waited here for weeks. Now you give me a rock and call it a magical talisman?nnDo I look like a child?
This doesn't make any sense! If there was a cure, why only give it to me?nnYou must be lying. I'm dying, and you just want to get rid of me!
You're mocking me!nnI'll kill you!nnI'll kill you and every Ashlander I see!
What is this? Do you think this little rock will help me?nnI need a cure, not baubles!
If... you're certain, I'll take it. Maybe it will work. nnWhat have I left to lose?nnYes, all right. I'll go.
Talisman… you insult me with this lie?  I know the Conclave gives false cures to the Blighted who seek their help.
I need a cure, not chicanery!
What is this?  This little rock will help me?nnI need a cure, not baubles!
If... you're certain.  Maybe it will work.nnYes, all right.  I'll go.
They're lying! You're lying! I won't leave until they give me the cure!
You just want me to die. You're trying to kill me!
Leave?  When they hold the secret to healing me somewhere in the Conclave?nnI refuse!
Is this how you aid the blighted?  I may be stricken but I can still kill you!
I won't leave until I'm cured!  Tell them to give me the cure that keeps them unblighted!
Without the cure I have nothing to lose!  Do your worst!
I won't leave until I'm cured! Tell them to give me whatever it is that protects them from affliction.
Boethiah? A Daedra? But I can't....nnI... I believe in the Tribunal. nnI know they can cure me. I just... I just need to speak to one of them.
That can't be true. I know they have a cure.nnLook at you! They let you in, and you're not sick. nnDidn't they give you a cure?

That doesn't make any sense. Boethiah is a Daedra! He's the Prince of Treason. Why would he help Ashlanders?nnHe must have tricked them. He wants to urn them away from the Tribunal.nnAlmalexia is the Merciful Healing Mother. She will cure me.

Leave? And go where? My family is dead. My house is buried in lava!nnMy children... when the madness took them, I had to... they were crazed. I had to do it with my own hands! Almalexia save me!nnEveryone says the Kagesh have a cure! Where is it?
All right, all right.  I'll go.
Ha ha.nnHa ha ha ha ha ha!nnThere's no hope! What does it matter anymore?nnDamn you to Malacath! Damn you and all the Ashlanders!

No, I must find out. House Dres cannot feign ignorance if something untoward comes to light.nnI cannot do this, but you could. The guards won't react kindly, but you look like you could handle them. nnFind the packages in the keep cellars.

You're not from around here, eh?nnOf course we farm maggots. The Green Pact doesn't allow us to grow crops, or clear land to graze slouchbears.nnDead meat and maggots, though.... We have plenty of those.
Eh? Well, it's a pact. An agreement between the Bosmer and the Green - the Valenwood, that is.nnThe gist is that we don't harm or exploit the plants of the wood. In return, the trees give us shelter.
Yes!  I could come with you.  I could carry your things.  Like a porter.  Or… or a squire.
Is there… nnOh.  Well.  nnIt's just… you're like no one anyone's met here before.  You're different.  This place will be smaller, duller after you're gone.
Oh.  nnOh, very well.  Fine, then.  Yes.  nnAnother time, then.  Safe travels.
You will?  You would?nnI'll look for you, Blightbane.  Safe travels!
I see.nnAll right, then… safe travels, Blightbane.

It is unclear to all involved exactly what transpired, but suffice it to say the Haven we knew is no more.nnA dark magic now pervades the town. Peering south one can see a massive, unearthly device towering over the walls. Its purpose is... unknown.

Aldmeri sank their ship and blocked up the harbor, so they went to ground in their palisade. It's across the creek to the west. nnTheir General Cruor is a bad one. He took all our stuff - so if you want stuff, the Palisade is the place to look.

Out of the east - first along the Trace from Haven Town, then along the coast in that sunken ship. nnIf you're looking to help Haven Town, I'd stick to the road. There are reports of strange noises and even walking trees in the woods to the east.

Set down next to me, enjoy the weather, and wave to Mister Mandibles when the old Thunderbug shows his head on that hill across the way. I've got some ooze-eel jerky here, and later maybe I could find us some Sun-Dusk Ale.nnOr are you more ambitious?

We kept herds of thunderbugs before the Imperials invaded Haven. The bastards just shot them up and left the corpses to rot!nnSeladair the maggot farmer might be happy about that, but where's it leave me, eh?

Like you herd anything else, I guess. Raise them from grubs, take good care of them. They're pretty loyal.nnThunderbugs take care of themselves. We let them wander the woods to forage for food, but they always come back at night to sleep.

Isn't it wonderful? Thistlewhip sent a hunter down with an armful of them. They're wild from the Thrambles, but they're so tame at birth, I can hand-feed them.nnIt will take time, but we'll be able to rebuild the herds the Imperials slaughtered.

Like you herd anything else, I guess. Raise them from grubs, take good care of them. They're pretty loyal.nnThunderbugs take care of themselves. We let them wander the woods to forage for food, but they always come back at night to sleep.

Our finest hunter. You won't find him here - since the city folk were pushed out of Haven, he and the other hunters moved to a camp north of the Refuge.nnThey've been trying to catch enough food in the Thrambles to keep us all fed.
It's one of the oldest sections of the wood. It's dark, overgrown, and twisty. Only the most experienced hunters dare enter. Anyone less skilled doesn't come back again.

The Bealton Raiders did it. The bastards slaughtered us all! We're just farmers. We didn't want a part in their war, but they didn't want witnesses.nnCurse Duke Baelborne and his men. I hope they're all rotting in Oblivion!

We hid in the cave when the soldiers came, hoping to escape. Gradwyn, Baelton, it didn't matter to us... we just wanted to be left alone.nnIt was the bastard Bealtons that killed us, after they killed all the Gradwyn. They didn't want witnesses.
What would you like to know?

It was all a big mistake. We came to town in Baron Gradwyn's name, looking for supplies. Duke Bealton's men were here doing the same.nnThe Bealtons outnumbered us. After we fell, those bastards slaughtered the townspeople.nnWe failed them all.

When the war with Shornhelm started, Duke Bealton sold out High Rock for gold. Daggerfall, Camlorn... they all felt his treachery.nnThe worst was when Duke Bealton executed Prince Gideon: Baron Gradwyn's son. There was no stopping things after that.

My liege, ruler of Glenpoint. Westtry's folk were his vassals, and we their protectors.nnAfter Duke Bealton executed Baron Gradwyn's son, Prince Gideon, the Baron was consumed by vengeance. It did not matter who fell - only that Gideon was avenged.

In life, I was a Knight of the Owl. Baron Gradwyn's man. That was 70 years ago. In death, I watch over the mournful souls of those who were slaughtered so long ago. Those we failed.nnOne day I hope we can finally rest... but I don't hold out hope.
That helm looks to be in remarkable condition. May I take a look?

I'm from Haven, the port to the southeast. The Imperials took it over.nnThey dug a big hole in the middle of the town. Down inside it they've built... eh, no one knows what, really. It's big, though. And creepy-looking.

The Aldmeri Dominion landed on the coast and captured Farwatch Tower.nnWe're fighting them up north. It's not going well.nnI'm not sure if any other runners met a worse fate. I've got a message to deliver. My wounds ache, but I'll be off again soon.
This is... very disturbing. Thank you for bringing it to me. Our incanabulists will need to look at this before we take action.

It's a barrow. Filled with bones.nnWe place the bones of our dead there once they've been... cleaned. You can find it just east of the Refuge.nnI have a lot of work to do before I can give my father to King Toad-Eye.

A great chief of our tribe, who lived long ago. He was interred in the Bonebarrow sometime in the First Era, and has protected it since.nnThose Bosmer who fancy themselves "civilized" call him King Faume. But we Razorvines know him better.
If you're looking for information about the kickbacks, I might be able to help you.  Meet me in the tavern alley after you talk to the Harbormaster.  Come alone.

House Father <<1>>?nnDare not utter accusations against your betters within these walls! Who are you to raise such a claim against our Great House?nnWhat proof have of this? Shall I call House Father <<1>> to answer these accusations?

He was killed by the Imperials when they invaded. He didn't live in Haven. He had Colovian friends there. When he heard they were under attack, he grabbed his bow and ran to help.nnYou were such a fool sometimes, dad.nnI miss you.

Villian! You raise your voice to the greatest champion of House Redoran! But now, I am nothing but dust within these walls.nnHow can I rest knowing the great House Redoran must struggle and bicker with the lesser Houses without my leadership?

My drupe-self is a duplicate, grown from a razorvine melon. She looks just like me, hm? If I were made of melon, anyway.nnShe's not intelligent, if that's what you're wondering. She just repeats the task I set her to do, over and over, tirelessly.

What happens every year, it seems. Someone invades, the Bosmer caper about with their sticks and stone knives, and eventually the Altmer will send a real army to save them.nnA great nuisance, if you ask me. Have you any wine? I could use a glass.

Perhaps they were running short of toothpicks. Perhaps they wanted to experience exotic new diseases from the Bosmer maids.nnWe fled Haven to hide in the woods, and I haven't had a decent meal since. They won't even let me pick the blasted melons.
Ah… yes. Very well. I've got some coin for you then.nnI believe I shall take my leave now. Thank you again.

A cave the east of the Refuge. The Bosmer bury people in it.nnBetween you and me, I seen Imperials taking bones out of there and carrying them south into Haven town. I can't figure what they want with them.

Burn this incense in the three sconces that encircle the outside of the temple.nnThey'll leave behind a powerful essence to enhance the ceremony.nnWhen you're done, meet me in the lower undercroft chambers.

By Vivec, what have you done? The Tribunal would see you executed for this!nnI must summon the House Father's spirit to divine the truth.nnAs his words will determine your fate, I will require your assistance in my ceremony.
And what proof would you bring to bear against House Dres? Shall I call the House Father to confront your accusations?
Hrrmph. Outsiders have no understanding of the jungle's way.nnSince you fight for me, I will share food with you.

We're keeping an eye on the invaders. Usually <<1>> is here running things, but she's scouting some orcs out in the Trace right now.nnToo bad she's away. It seems there are even stranger things away to the south.

Well, some say that fallen logs stand and walk.nnYou might laugh, but this is the Grahtwood. Even for those who live here, what comes out of the forest can surprise. Who knows where such things come from?

Two fisherman out on the water saw Lea jump from the cliffs, but when they came ashore, her body was gone.nnShe killed herself because of my lie. Her death was my fault. I can't rest until I bring her peace.

She was engaged to Lord Gette of Aldcroft. What were we thinking, falling in love? That's youth for you.nnLea's parents wouldn't think of marrying their daughter to a common fisherman. I should have known. nnEven so, Lea refused to leave me.

If Lea stayed with me, she'd have nothing but a life of hard labor and poverty. nnI told her to marry Lord Gette. I told her I didn't love her anymore. I thought the lie would free her.nnOne day later, she threw herself from the cliffs of High Rock.

Adrone said he loved me. He promised he'd never leave me. He lied.nnMy body is lost. It is Lord Gette's now. What I kept from him in life, Lord Gette took from me in death.nnOne cannot deny the cruel desires of a necromancer.

Yes. I have watched my Adrone these long years. He never stopped looking. He never strayed from me, never in thirty years. I wish only to end his guilt and grief.nnPlease, tell Adrone I am at peace. I wait for him.nnLord Gette owns me no more.

My body is buried beneath the island where Lord Gette last... used me.nnHe is dead twenty years now, but his curse holds me still.nnMy spirit is fettered to my body. I cannot rest. Sometimes, I watch Adrone. Sometimes, there is only darkness.

As long as my spirit and body are seperate, I will have no peace.nnGo to the island to the west. Look for a pile of dirt. Dig to find Lord Gette's secret. He hid it from the light.nnFind and destroy my body. Only then can you lift Lord Gette's curse.
You should take it to Warden Brehat in Deleyn's Mill as soon as possible.

I am Inana, former Archmaster of House Redoran. It seems so long ago that I led this House, yet only now have I stirred from my rest.nnI sense dark times will come to pass, and my spirit doubts House Redoran will survive unscathed.
Psh! House Indoril, Telvanni, and the like. They think themselves our equals, when only Redoran is truly blessed by the Three.
Truly, I know not. Perhaps I will be cursed to watch as my House falls into ruin. Or blessed to attend the proud reclamation of our glory.

The Wyrd Tree is healing. You've restored purity to our glen and removed its corruption. Now I can wait for my sisters to return.nnWe breathe with new life, thanks to you.nnWe will never forget you, <<1>>.
A most terrible premonition, memories past rising to scar me once again. I smelled the ashes of Red Mountain descending upon House Redoran, smothering all beneath its coals.

I feel your words are true. And I see that you are no normal mortal as well.nnI will return to my rest, and trust that House Redoran has the support of such blessed champions as you. Though how many may count themselves as... a Numinous?
